\id SIR Original Douay-Rheims Bible
\ide UTF-8
\h Ecclesiasticus
\mt1 Ecclesiasticus.
\c 1
\p
\v 1 All wisdom is of our Lord God, & hath been always with him, & is before all time.
\v 2 The sand of the sea, & the drops of rain, & the days of the world, who hath numbered? The height of heaven, and breadth of the earth, & profundity of the depth, who hath measured? \f + \fr 1:2 \ft Man's wisdom is not able to comprehend the works of God.\f*
\v 3 The wisdom of God that goeth before all things, who hath searched out?
\v 4 Wisdom was created before all things, & the understanding of prudence from everlasting.
\v 5 Afountain of wisdom the word of God on high, and the entrance thereof everlasting commandments.
\v 6 The root of wisdom to whom hath it been revealed, & the subtilties thereof who hath known?
\v 7 The discipline of wisdom to whom hath it been revealed and made manifest, and the multiplication of her entrance who hath understood.
\v 8 There is one most high Creator omnipotent, and mighty King, and to be feared exceedingly, sitting upon his throne & the God of dominion.
\v 9 He created her in the Holy Ghost, and hath seen, and numbered, and measured her.
\v 10 And he hath poured her out upon all his works, and upon all flesh according to his gift, and hath given her to them that fear him.
\v 11 The fear of our Lord is glory, and gloriation, and joy, and a crown of exultation. \f + \fr 1:11 \ft Eternal glory is the fruit of the fear of our Lord: not that this one virtue sufficeth, but it is the beginning, grounded in true faith, and bringeth forth other virtues, divine gifts with the fruits of the Holy Ghost, & a joyful crown in the end.\f*
\v 12 The fear of our Lord shall delight the heart, and shall give joy, and gladness, and length of days.
\v 13 With him that feareth our Lord it shall be well in the later end, and in the day of his death he shall be blessed.
\v 14 The love of God is honourable wisdom.
\v 15 But they to whom she shall appear in vision, they love her in the vision, and in the agnizing of her great works.
\v 16 The fear of our Lord is the beginning of wisdom, and was created with the faithful in the womb, and goeth with the elect women, and is known with the just & faithful.
\v 17 The fear of our Lord is religiosity of knowledge. \x + \xo 1:17 \xt Prov. 1. &. 9.\x*
\v 18 Religiosity shall keep and justify the heart, shall give joy and gladness.
\v 19 With him that feareth our Lord it shall be well, and in the days of his consummation he shall be blessed.
\v 20 The fullness of wisdom is to fear God, and fullness is of the fruits thereof.
\v 21 All her house she shall fill with her generations, and the store-houses with her treasures.
\v 22 Acrown of wisdom, the fear of our Lord, replenishing peace, and the fruit of salvation:
\v 23 and hath seen, and numbered her: but both are the gifts of God.
\v 24 Wisdom shall distribute knowledge, and understanding of prudence: and exalteth the glory of them that hold it.
\v 25 The root of wisdom is to fear our Lord: for the boughs thereof are of long time.
\v 26 in the treasures of wisdom is understanding, & religiosity of knowledge: but to sinners wisdom is abomination.
\v 27 The fear of our Lord expelleth sin:
\v 28 for he that is without fear, cannot be justified: for the anger of his animosity, is his subversion.
\v 29 Until a time the patient shall sustain, and after shall be rewarded of joyfulness.
\v 30 Agood understanding will hide his words until a time, and the lips of many shall shew forth his understanding.
\v 31 In the treasures of wisdom is signification of discipline:
\v 32 But the worship of God is abomination to a sinner. \f + \fr 1:32 \ft Men drowned in sin think the service of God a most tedious & loathsome thing.\f*
\v 33 Son, coveting wisdom, keep justice, & God will give her to thee.
\v 34 For the fear of our Lord is wisdom and discipline: and that which well pleaseth him,
\v 35 is faith, and meekness, and he will fill his treasures.
\v 36 Be not incredulous to the fear of our Lord: and come not to him with a double heart.
\v 37 Be not an hypocrite in the sight of men, and be not scandalized in thy lips.
\v 38 Attend to them, lest perhaps thou fall, and bring dishonour to thy soul,
\v 39 and God reveal thy secrets, and in the midst of the synagogue cast thee down:
\v 40 because thou camest to our Lord wickedly, & thy heart is full of guile and deceit.
\c 2
\p
\v 1 Son, coming to the service of God, stand in justice, and in fear, & prepare thy soul to tentation.
\v 2 Repress thy heart, & sustain: incline thine ear, & receive the words of understanding, and make no haste in the time of obduction. \f + \fr 2:2 \ft Desire not to die that thou mayst thereby be covered from worldly miseries, for that is a desperate desire, but have patience in this life that thou mayst find rest in God.\f* \f + \fr 2:2 \ft * Covering.\f*
\v 3 Sustain the sustentations of God: be joined to God, and sustain, that thy life may increase in the later end.
\v 4 All that shall be applied to thee, receive: and in sorrow sustain, and in thy humiliation have patience:
\v 5 for gold and silver are tried in the fire, but acceptable men in the furnace of humiliation.
\v 6 Believe God, and he will recover thee: and direct thy way, and hope in him. Keep his fear, and grow old therein.
\v 7 Ye that fear our Lord, expect his mercy: & decline not from him, lest ye fall.
\v 8 Ye that fear our Lord, believe him, & your reward shall not be void.
\v 9 Ye that fear our Lord hope in him: and mercy shall come to you for your delectation.
\v 10 Ye that fear our Lord, love him, & your hearts shall be illuminated.
\v 11 Children behold the nations of men: and know ye that none hath hoped in our Lord, and hath been confounded.
\v 12 For who hath continued in his commandment, and hath been forsaken? Or who hath invocated him, and he despised him?
\v 13 Because God is pitiful and merciful, and will forgive sins in the day of tribulation: and he is protector to all that seek him in truth.
\v 14 Woe to them of a double heart, & to wicked lips, and to the hands that do evil, and to the sinner that goeth on the earth two ways. \f + \fr 2:14 \ft As virtues are to be rewarded: so all sins shall be punished. Namely external pretence of holiness, with secret evil intention. Distrust in God. Impatience, and the like.\f*
\v 15 Woe to them that be dissolute of heart, which believe not God: and therefore they shall not be protected of him.
\v 16 Woe be to them, that have lost patience, and that have forsaken the right ways, and have declined into perverse ways.
\v 17 And what will they do, when our Lord shall begin to look on them?
\v 18 They that fear our Lord, will not be incredulous to his word: and they that love him, will keep his way.
\v 19 They that fear our Lord, will seek after the things that are well pleasing to him: and they that love him, shall be filled with his law.
\v 20 They that fear our Lord, will prepare their hearts, and in his sight will sanctify their souls.
\v 21 They that fear our Lord, keep his commandments, and will have patience even until his visitation,
\v 22 saying: If we do not penance, we shall fall into the hands of our Lord, and not into the hands of men.
\v 23 For according to his greatness, so also his mercy is with him.
\c 3
\p
\v 1 The children of wisdom are the Church of the just: and their nation, obedience and love. \f + \fr 3:1 \ft The progeny of God's children bring forth the fruit of obedience and love.\f*
\v 2 Hear your father's judgement o children, and so do that you may be saved. \f + \fr 3:2 \ft Honour and estimation of parents is the chiefest obligation that man hath towards his neighbour, & the first after his duty to God.\f*
\v 3 For God hath honoured the father in the children: and inquiring of the mother's judgement, hath confirmed it upon the children.
\v 4 He that loveth God, praying shall obtain for sins, and shall refrain himself from them, and shall be heard in the prayer of days.
\v 5 And as he that gathereth treasure, so he also that honoureth his mother.
\v 6 He that honoureth his father, shall have joy in children, and in the day of his prayer he shall be heard.
\v 7 He that honoureth his father, shall live the longer life: & he that obeyeth the father, shall refresh the mother.
\v 8 He that feareth our Lord honoureth his parents, and as his lords he will serve them that begat him. \x + \xo 3:8 \xt Exo. 20. Deut. 5.\x*
\v 9 In work and word, & all patience honour thy father,
\v 10 that blessing may come upon thee from him, & his blessing may remain in the later end. \x + \xo 3:10 \xt Gen. 27. & 49.\x*
\v 11 The father's blessing establisheth the houses of the children: but the mother's curse rooteth up the foundation.
\v 12 Glory not in the contumely of thy father: for his confusion is no glory to thee.
\v 13 For the glory of a man is by the honour of his father, and the father without honour is the dishonour of the son.
\v 14 Son receive the old age of thy father, and make him not sorrowful in his life:
\v 15 and if he fail in understanding, pardon him, and despise him not in thy strength: for the alms to the father shall not be in oblivion.
\v 16 For good shall be restored thee for the sin of thy mother, \f + \fr 3:16 \ft Alms given, or prayer made, or sacrifice offered for parents, doth merit reward at God's hand.\f*
\v 17 and in justice it shall be builded to thee, and in the day of tribulation there shall be remembrance of thee: and as ice in the clear weather shall thy sins melt away.
\v 18 Of what an evil fame is he, that forsaketh his father: and he is cursed of God, that doth exasperate his mother.
\v 19 Son do thy works in meekness, and thou shalt be beloved above the glory of men. \x + \xo 3:19 \xt Phil. 2.\x*
\v 20 The greater thou art, humble thyself in all things, and thou shalt find grace before God: \f + \fr 3:20 \ft All greatness in men proceeding from God, bindeth them so much the more to humility, which virtue God most specially loveth: that so they may shew gratitude for his benefits.\f*
\v 21 because the might of God only is great, and he is honoured of the humble.
\v 22 Seek not things higher than thyself, and search not things stronger than thy hability: but the things that God hath commanded thee, think on them always, and in many of his works be not curious. \x + \xo 3:22 \xt Pro. 25. v. 2.\x*
\v 23 For it is not necessary for thee, to see with thine eyes those things that are hid.
\v 24 In superfluous things search not many ways, and in many of his works thou shalt not be curious.
\v 25 For very many things are shewed to thee above the understanding of men.
\v 26 Many also have their suspicion supplanted, and have held their senses in vanity.
\v 27 Ahard heart shall fare ill in the later end, and he that loveth danger, shall perish in it. \f + \fr 3:27 \ft Those that dare live in sinful state, tempting God even to the last hour, commonly perish therein.\f*
\v 28 Aheart that goeth two ways, shall not have success, and the perverse of heart shall be scandalized in them.
\v 29 Awicked heart shall be laden with sorrows, and the sinner will add to commit sin.
\v 30 To the synagogue of the proud there shall be no health: for the shrub of sin shall be rooted up in them, and it shall not be perceived.
\v 31 The heart of the wise is understood in wisdom, and a good ear will hear wisdom with all desire.
\v 32 Awise heart, and that which hath understanding will abstain it-self from sins, and in the works of justice shall have success.
\v 33 Water quencheth burning fire, and alms resisteth sins: \x + \xo 3:33 \xt Dan. 4. v. 24.\x*
\v 34 and God is the beholder of him that rendereth grace: he remembereth him afterward, and in the time of his fall he shall find a sure stay.
\c 4
\p
\v 1 Son defraud not the alms of the poor, and turn not away thine eyes from the poor.
\v 2 Despise not the hungry soul: and exasperate not the poor in his poverty.
\v 3 Afflict not the heart of the needy, & defer not the gift to him that is in distress.
\v 4 Reject not the petition of him that is afflicted: and turn not away thy face from the needy.
\v 5 From the poor turn not away thine eyes for anger: and leave not to them that ask of thee, to curse thee behind thy back. \f + \fr 4:5 \ft Give not occasion by thy hard dealing with the poor, that they curse thee.\f*
\v 6 For the prayer of him that curseth thee in the bitterness of his soul shall be heard: and he that made him, will hear him. \f + \fr 4:6 \ft For if thou give cause, God who is their protector, will revenge them against thee.\f*
\v 7 Make thyself affable to the congregation of the poor, and to the ancient humble thy soul, and to a great man bow thy head.
\v 8 Bow down thine ear to the poor without sadness, and render thy debt, and answer him peaceable words in mildness.
\v 9 Deliver him that suffereth injury out of the hand of the proud: and be not faint-hearted in thy soul.
\v 10 In judging be merciful to pupils as a father, & as an husband to their mother:
\v 11 and thou shalt be as the obedient son of the Highest, and he will have mercy on thee more than a mother.
\v 12 Wisdom inspireth life to her children, and receiveth them that seek after her, and will go before them in the way of justice.
\v 13 And he that loveth her, loveth life: and they that shall watch to her, shall embrace her sweetness.
\v 14 They that shall hold her, shall inherit life: and whither-soever he shall enter, God will bless him.
\v 15 They that serve her, shall be servants to the holy: and them that love her God loveth.
\v 16 He that heareth her, shall judge nations: and he that beholdeth her, shall remain confident.
\v 17 If he believe her, he shall inherit her, and her creatures shall be in confirmation: \f + \fr 4:17 \ft They that follow wisdom shall be safe.\f*
\v 18 because in tentation she walketh with him, and first of all she chooseth him.
\v 19 Fear, and dread, and probation she will bring upon him: and she will torment him in the tribulation of her doctrine, till she try him in her cogitations and credit his soul.
\v 20 And she will establish him, and make a direct way unto him, and rejoice him,
\v 21 and will disclose her secrets to him, and will heap upon him as treasures knowledge & understanding of justice.
\v 22 But if he go amiss, she will forsake him, and deliver him into the hands of his enemy.
\v 23 Son observe time, and avoid from evil.
\v 24 For thy soul be not ashamed to say the truth.
\v 25 For there is shame that bringeth sin, & there is shame that bringeth glory and grace. \f + \fr 4:25 \ft Through shamefastness to yield unto sin, or not to reprove sin, is vicious.\f* \f + \fr 4:25 \ft But to be ashamed, and to abhor sin is very good and necessary.\f*
\v 26 Accept no face against thine own face, nor against thy soul a lie.
\v 27 Reverence not thy neighbour in his offence:
\v 28 nor keep in a word in time of salvation. Hide not thy wisdom in the beauty thereof.
\v 29 For by the tongue wisdom is discerned: and understanding, and knowledge, and doctrine by the word of the wise, and steadfastness in the works of justice.
\v 30 Do not gainsay the word of truth by any means: and be ashamed of the lie of thine unskillfulness. \f + \fr 4:30 \ft All men are bound to say the truth at convenient times, v. 23. And ever bound to avoid untruths.\f*
\v 31 Be not ashamed to confess thy sins, and submit not thyself to every man for sin.
\v 32 Resist not against the face of the mighty, neither labour against the stream of the river.
\v 33 For justice contend for thy soul, and unto death strive for justice, and God will overthrow thine enemies for thee. \f + \fr 4:33 \ft Every one is bound rather to loose his life, than to do against justice, or to deny the truth.\f*
\v 34 Be not hasty in thy tongue: and unprofitable and remiss in thy works.
\v 35 Be not as a lion in thy house, overthrowing them of thy household, and oppressing them that are subject to thee.
\v 36 Let not thine hand be stretched out to receive, and closed to give.
\c 5
\p
\v 1 Attend not to unjust possessions, and say not: I have sufficient livelihood: for it shall nothing profit in the time of vengeance & affliction.
\v 2 Follow not in thy strength the concupiscence of thy heart: \f + \fr 5:2 \ft After that sin is forgiven there remaineth oftentimes punishment for satisfaction.\f*
\v 3 and say not: How mighty am I? And who shall bring me under for my facts? For God revenging will revenge. \f + \fr 5:3 \ft Though thou be so potent, that no man can hinder thy evil designment; yet do it not, because God will punish it.\f*
\v 4 Say not: I have sinned, and what sorrowful thing hath chanced to me? For the Highest is a patient rewarder.
\v 5 Of sin forgiven be not without fear, neither add thou sin upon sin.
\v 6 And say not: The mercy of our Lord is great, he will have mercy on the multitude of my sins.
\v 7 For mercy and wrath quickly approach from God, and his wrath looketh upon sinners.
\v 8 Slack not to be converted to our Lord, and defer not from day to day.
\v 9 For his wrath shall come suddenly: and in the time of vengeance he will destroy thee.
\v 10 Be not careful in unjust riches: for they shall not profit thee in the day of obduction and vengeance. \f + \fr 5:10 \ft * Covering, or death. Prov. 10. v. 4.\f*
\v 11 Toss not thyself into every wind, and go not into every way: for so every sinner is proved by a double tongue.
\v 12 Be steadfast in the way of our Lord, & in the truth of thy understanding, and in knowledge, and let the word of peace and justice accompany thee. \f + \fr 5:12 \ft Constancy in good purpose meriteth\f* \f + \fr 5:12 \ft the promised peace, and just reward.\f*
\v 13 Be mild to hear the word, thou mayst understand, and with wisdom utter thou a true answer.
\v 14 If thou have understanding, answer thy neighbour: but if not, let thine hand be upon thy mouth, lest thou be taken in an unskillful word, and be confounded.
\v 15 Honour and glory in the word of the wise, but the tongue of the unwise is his subversion.
\v 16 Be not called a whisperer, and be not taken in thy tongue, & confounded.
\v 17 For upon a thief is confusion & repentance, and a very evil condemnation upon the double tongued, but to the whisperer hatred, and enmity, and contumely.
\v 18 Justify thou the little one, and the great alike.
\c 6
\p
\v 1 Be not for a friend made an enemy to thy neighbour: for the evil man shall inherit reproach and contumely, and every sinner envious and double tongued.
\v 2 Extol not thyself in the cogitation of thy soul as it were a bull: lest perhaps thy strength be quashed,
\v 3 and it eat thy leaves, and destroy thy fruits, and thou be left as a dry tree in the wilderness.
\v 4 For a wicked soul shall destroy him that hath it, and it giveth him to be a joy to his enemies, and shall lead him into the lot of the impious.
\v 5 A sweet word multiplieth friends, & appeaseth enemies, and a gracious tongue in a good man aboundeth. \f + \fr 6:5 \ft So Gedeon pacified the Ephraimites; that were incensed against him. Iudic. 8.\f*
\v 6 Let there be many at peace with thee, and let one of a thousand be thy counseller.
\v 7 If thou possess a friend, in tentation possess him, and not easily credit him.
\v 8 For he is a friend according to his own time, and will not abide in the day of tribulation
\v 9 And there is a friend that is turned to enmity: and there is a friend that will disclose hatred, and reproaches.
\v 10 And there is a friend companion at the table, and he will not abide in the day of necessity.
\v 11 Afriend if he continue steadfast, shall be to thee as an equal, and in them of thy household shall deal confidently:
\v 12 if he humble himself against thee, and hide himself from thy face, thou shalt have friendship of one accord for good.
\v 13 Be separated from thine enemies, & take heed of thy friends.
\v 14 Afaithful friend, is a strong protection: and he that hath found him, hath found a treasure.
\v 15 To a faithful friend there is no comparison, and there is no poise of gold and silver able to countervail the goodness of his fidelity.
\v 16 Afaithful friend, is the medicine of life & immortality: & they that fear our Lord, shall find him.
\v 17 He that feareth God, shall likewise have good friendship: because according to him shall his friend be.
\v 18 Son, from thy youth receive doctrine, and even to thy hoar hairs thou shalt find wisdom.
\v 19 As he that ploweth, and that soweth, go to her, and expect her good fruits.
\v 20 For in her work thou shalt labour a little, and shalt quickly eat of her generation.
\v 21 How exceeding sharp is wisdom to the unlearned men, and the unwise will not continue in her.
\v 22 As the virtue of a stone she shall be a probation in them, and they will not stay to cast her forth.
\v 23 For the wisdom of doctrine is according to her name, and she is not manifest to many, but to whom she is known, she continueth even to the sight of God. \f + \fr 6:23 \ft Many prefer learning before piety, which S. Augustin reproveth, preferring the godly before the learned that are less virtuous: The unlearned rise (saith he) and take the Kingdom of heaven, and we with our learning without heart, lo how we tumble in the durt. li. 8. c. 8. Confess.\f*
\v 24 Hear my son, and take counsel of understanding, and cast not away my counsel.
\v 25 Thrust thy foot into her fetters, and thy neck into her chains.
\v 26 Put under thy shoulder, and carry her, and be not weary of her bands.
\v 27 With all thy mind go to her, and with all thy strength keep her ways.
\v 28 Search her out, and she shall be made manifest to thee, and having obtained her, forsake her not:
\v 29 For in the later end, thou shalt find rest in her, and she shall be turned unto delectation.
\v 30 And her fetters shall be to thee for a protection of strength, and foundation of power, & her chains for a stole of glory:
\v 31 For the beauty of life is in her, and her bands are a healthful binding.
\v 32 Thou shalt put on her a stole of glory, and as a crown of gratulation thou shalt set her upon thee.
\v 33 Son, if thou attend to me, thou shalt learn: and if thou wilt apply thy mind, thou shalt be wise.
\v 34 If thou wilt incline thine ear, thou shalt receive doctrine: and if thou love to hear, thou shalt be wise.
\v 35 Stand in the multitude of wise ancients, and be joined to their wisdom from thy heart, that thou mayst hear all the narration of God, and the praise may not escape thee.
\v 36 And if thou see a wise man, watch after him, and let thy foot wear the steps of his doors.
\v 37 Have thy cogitation in the precepts of God, and in his commandments most of all be daily conversant: and he will give thee heart, and the desire of wisdom shall be given thee.
\c 7
\p
\v 1 Do not evils, and they shall not apprehend thee. \f + \fr 7:1 \ft Whatsoever any soweth that he shall reap, and the wicked shall eat the fruits of his own works.\f*
\v 2 Depart from the wicked, & evil shall fail from thee. \x + \xo 7:2 \xt Iob. 9.\x*
\v 3 Son, sow not evils in the furrows of justice, & thou shalt not reap them sevenfold. \x + \xo 7:3 \xt Ps. 142.\x*
\v 4 Seek not of the Lord chief principality, nor of the king the chair of honour. \x + \xo 7:4 \xt Eccl. 7.\x*
\v 5 Justify not thy-self before God, because he is the knower of the heart: and before the king desire not to seem wise.
\v 6 Seek not to be made a judge, unless thou be able by power to break iniquities: lest perhaps thou fear the face of the mighty, and put a scandal in thine equity. \f + \fr 7:6 \ft Great prudence and fortitude are required in all Judges spiritual and temporal.\f*
\v 7 Sin not against the multitude of a city, neither thrust thy-self into the people,
\v 8 nor bind together double sins: for neither in one shalt thou be free from punishment.
\v 9 Be not faint-hearted in thy mind:
\v 10 despise not to pray, and to give alms.
\v 11 Say not: In the multitude of my gifts God will have respect, and when I offer to God most high, he will receive my gifts.
\v 12 Laugh not a man to scorn in the bitterness of his soul: for there is that humbleth and exalteth, God the overseer of all.
\v 13 Plow not a lie against thy brother: neither do thou likewise against thy friend.
\v 14 Be not willing to make any lie: for the custom thereof is not good.
\v 15 Be not full of words in a multitude of ancients, and iterate not a word in thy speech. \f + \fr 7:15 \ft In hell are two punishments: fire burning, and the worm of conscience vexing the soul, & both are eternal.\f*
\v 16 Hate not laborious works, and husbandry created of the Highest.
\v 17 Count not thyself in the multitude of men without discipline.
\v 18 Be mindful of wrath, because it will not slack.
\v 19 Humble thy spirit very much: because the vengeance of the flesh of the impious, is fire and the worm.
\v 20 Do not prevaricate against thy friend deferring money, nor despise thy dearest brother for gold.
\v 21 Depart not from a wise and good woman, which thou hast gotten in the fear of our Lord: for the grace of her bashfulness is above gold.
\v 22 Hurt not the servant that worketh in truth, nor the hired man that giveth his soul. \x + \xo 7:22 \xt Levi. 19.\x*
\v 23 Let a wise servant be beloved of thee as thy soul, defraud him not of liberty, nor leave him needy.
\v 24 Hast thou cattle? Look well to them: and if they be profitable, let them continue with thee.
\v 25 Hast thou children? Instruct them, & bow them from their childhood.
\v 26 Hast thou daughters? Keep their body, and shew not thy countenance merry towards them.
\v 27 Bestow thy daughter, and thou shalt do a great work, and give her to a wise man.
\v 28 If thou have a wife according to thy soul, cast her not off: and to her that is hateful commit not thyself. With thy whole heart
\v 29 honour thy father, and forget not the groanings of thy mother: \x + \xo 7:29 \xt Tob. 4.\x*
\v 30 remember that thou hadst not been born but by them: and recompense them, as they also thee.
\v 31 In all thy soul fear our Lord, and sanctify his Priests. \x + \xo 7:31 \xt Deu. 12.\x*
\v 32 With all thy strength love him that made thee: & forsake not his ministers.
\v 33 Honour God with all thy soul, and honour the Priests, and purge thyself with the arms.
\v 34 Give them the portion, as it is commanded thee, of the first fruits and purgation: and of thy negligence purge thyself with few. \x + \xo 7:34 \xt Levit. 2. Num. 18.\x*
\v 35 The gift of thine arms and the sacrifice of sanctification thou shalt offer to our Lord, and the first of holy things:
\v 36 and to the poor stretch out thine hand, that thy propitiation may be perfected, and thy blessing.
\v 37 The grace of a gift is in the sight of all the living, and from the dead stay not grace. \f + \fr 7:37 \ft Works of mercy are also profitable to the dead, as prayer, alms, and sacrifice for souls in purgatory.\f*
\v 38 Want not in consolation to them that weep, and walk with them that mourn. \x + \xo 7:38 \xt Rom. 12. v. 15.\x*
\v 39 Be not loath to visit the sick: for by these things thou shalt be confirmed in love.
\v 40 In all thy works remember thy later ends, and thou wilt not sin for ever. \f + \fr 7:40 \ft Amost especial preservative from sin.\f*
\c 8
\p
\v 1 Strive not with a mighty man, lest perhaps thou fall into his hands.
\v 2 Contend not with a rich man, lest perhaps he make an action against thee.
\v 3 For gold and silver hath destroyed many, and hath reached even to the heart of kings, and hath turned them. \f + \fr 8:3 \ft Bribery sometimes corrupteth Kings, much more other inferior Judges. And therefore it is better to suffer damage than to contend by law against the rich.\f*
\v 4 Strive not with a man full of tongue, & thou shalt not heap sticks upon his fire.
\v 5 Communicate not with the ignorant man, lest he speak ill of thy progeny.
\v 6 Despise not a man that turneth himself from sin, nor upbraid him therewith: remember that we are all in state to be blamed. \x + \xo 8:6 \xt Gal. 6.\x*
\v 7 Despise not a man in his old age: for we also shall become old.
\v 8 Rejoice not of thine enemy dead: knowing that we do all die, & would not that others should joy thereat.
\v 9 Despise not the narration of wise ancients, and in their proverbs be thou conversant.
\v 10 For of them thou shalt learn wisdom, and doctrine of understanding, and to serve great men without blame.
\v 11 Let not the narration of the ancients escape thee: for they learned of their fathers:
\v 12 because of them thou shalt learn understanding, and in time of necessity to give answer.
\v 13 Kindle not the coals of sinners rebuking them, and be not kindled with the flame of the fire of their sins. \x + \xo 8:13 \xt Prov. 26.\x*
\v 14 Stand not against the face of a contumelious person, lest he sit as a spy in wait for thy mouth.
\v 15 Lend not to a man mightier than thyself, and if thou doest lend, count it as lost.
\v 16 Be not surety above thy power: and if thou be surety, think as if thou were to pay it.
\v 17 Judge not against a judge: because he judgeth according to that which is just.
\v 18 With the audacious go not on the way, lest perhaps he burden thee with his evils: for he goeth according to his own will, and thou shalt perish together with his folly.
\v 19 With an angry man make no brawl, and with the audacious go not into the desert: because blood is as nothing before him, and where there is no help, he will overthrow thee. \x + \xo 8:19 \xt Prov. 22. v. 24.\x*
\v 20 Confer no counsel with fools, for they cannot love but such things as please them. \f + \fr 8:20 \ft In all consultations confer with the skillful; for the blind cannot judge of colours, the deaf of music, the sick of taste: nor worldly men of spiritual things.\f*
\v 21 Before a stranger do no matter of counsel: for thou knowest not what he will bring forth.
\v 22 Make not thy heart manifest to every man: lest perhaps he repay thee false kindness, and speak reproachfully to thee.
\c 9
\p
\v 1 Be not jealous over the wife of thy bosom, lest she shew upon thee the malice of wicked doctrine. \f + \fr 9:1 \ft Seeing jealousy between man & wife is dangerous, much more unnecessary conversation between other men and women, especially probable occasions of sin must be avoided.\f*
\v 2 Give not to a woman the power of thy soul, lest she go in thy strength, and thou be confounded.
\v 3 Look not upon a woman that is desirous of many: lest perhaps thou fall into her snares.
\v 4 With her that is a dancer be not daily conversant, nor hear her, lest perhaps thou perish in her efficacy. \x + \xo 9:4 \xt Prov. 5.\x*
\v 5 Behold not a virgin, lest perhaps thou be scandalized in her beauty.
\v 6 Give not thy soul to harlots in any point: lest thou destroy thyself, and thine inheritance.
\v 7 Look not round about in the ways of the city, nor wander up and down in the streets thereof.
\v 8 Turn away thy face from a trimmed woman, and gaze not about upon another's beauty.
\v 9 By the beauty of a woman many have perished: and hereby concupiscence is inflamed as a fire.
\v 10 Every woman, that is an harlot, shall be trodden upon as dung in the way.
\v 11 Many having admired the beauty of another man's wife, have become reprobate, for her communication burneth as fire.
\v 12 Sit not at all with another man's wife, nor repose upon the bed with her:
\v 13 and strive not with her at the wine, lest perhaps thy heart decline toward her, & with thy blood thou fall into perdition.
\v 14 Forsake not an old friend: for the new will not be like to him. \f + \fr 9:14 \ft Constancy in good things, namely in friendship, is very necessary.\f*
\v 15 Anew friend, is as new wine: it shall wax old, and thou shalt drink it with sweetness.
\v 16 Do not zealously desire the glory and the riches of a sinner: for thou knowest not what his subversion shall be. \f + \fr 9:16 \ft Asinner that prospereth is like to a summer flower in the field, that is quickly cut down, and withereth.\f*
\v 17 Let not the injury of the unjust please thee, knowing that even to hell the impious shall not please.
\v 18 Be far from the man that hath power to kill, and thou shalt not suspect the fear of death.
\v 19 And if thou come to him, commit nothing, lest perhaps he take away thy life.
\v 20 Know it to be communication with death; because thou shalt go in the midst of snares, and shalt walk upon the weapons of the sorrowful.
\v 21 According to thy power beware thee of thy neighbour, and treat with the wise and prudent.
\v 22 Let just men be thy guests, and let thy gloriation be in the fear of God,
\v 23 and let the cogitation of God be in thy understanding, & all thine enarration in the precepts of the Highest.
\v 24 Works shall be praised in the hands of artificers, and the Prince of the people in the wisdom of his speech, but the word of the ancients in the sense.
\v 25 Aman full of tongue is terrible in his city, and he that is rash in his word shall be odious.
\c 10
\p
\v 1 A wise judge shall judge his people, and the principality of the wise shall be stable. \x + \xo 10:1 \xt Pro. 29.\x*
\v 2 According to the judge of the people, so also are his ministers: and what manner of man the ruler of a city is, such also are the inhabitants therein. \f + \fr 10:2 \ft Example of rulers is of great efficacy.\f*
\v 3 An unwise king shall destroy his people: and cities shall be inhabited by the understanding of the prudent.
\v 4 The power of the earth is in the hand of God, and he will raise up a profitable ruler for a time over it.
\v 5 The prosperity of man is in the hand of God, & upon the face of the scribe he will put his honour.
\v 6 Any injury of thy neighbour remember not, and do nothing by works of injury.
\v 7 Pride is odious before God and men: and all the iniquity of the nations is execrable. \x + \xo 10:7 \xt Dan. 4.\x*
\v 8 A kingdom is translated from nation unto nation, because of injustices, and injuries, and contumelies, and diverse deceits. \f + \fr 10:8 \ft The causes of translating Kingdoms, & dominions.\f*
\v 9 But nothing is more wicked than the covetous man. Why is earth and ashes proud? \f + \fr 10:9 \ft Covetousness is the root of all evils, 1. Tim. 6. in that for lucre many fall into all sorts of sins, even into schism and heresy. erring from the faith. ibid. v. 10.\f*
\v 10 Nothing is more wicked than to love money. For he hath his soul also to sell: because in his life he hath cast forth his most inward things:
\v 11 All power is of short life. Long sickness grieveth the Physician.
\v 12 Short sickness the Physician cutteth off at the first: so also the king is today, & tomorrow he shall die.
\v 13 For when a man shall die, he shall inherit serpents, and beasts, and worms.
\v 14 The beginning of the pride of man, is to apostatate from God:
\v 15 because his heart is departed from him that made him, for pride is the beginning of all sin: he that holdeth it, shall be filled with curses, & it shall subvert him in the end. \f + \fr 10:15 \ft Nevertheless pride is the beginning of all sin, as this text expressly testifieth: and the reason is, for that man's inordinate self-love is the cause of declining from God's commandments: & they which run on in that course, cast themselves headlong into the depth of all mischief, and of eternal misery.\f*
\v 16 Therefore hath our Lord dishonoured the congregations of the evil, & hath destroyed them even to the end.
\v 17 God hath destroyed the seats of proud Princes, and hath made the meek sit in their stead.
\v 18 God hath made the roots of the proud nations to wither, and hath planted the humble of the nations themselves.
\v 19 Our Lord hath subverted the lands of the gentiles, and hath destroyed them even to the foundation.
\v 20 He hath made of them to wither, and hath destroyed them, and hath made the memory of them to cease from the earth.
\v 21 God hath destroyed the memory of the proud, and hath left the memory of them that are humble in understanding.
\v 22 Pride was not created to men: nor wrath to the nation of women.
\v 23 That seed of men shall be honoured, which feareth God: but that seed shall be dishonoured, which transgresseth the commandments of our Lord.
\v 24 In the midst of brethren their ruler shall be in honour: and they that fear our Lord, shall be in his eyes.
\v 25 The glory of the rich, of the honourable, and of the poor, is the fear of God:
\v 26 Despise not the just man that is poor, and magnify not the sinful man that is rich.
\v 27 The great one, and the judge, and the mighty is in honour, and there is none greater than he that feareth God.
\v 28 Free men will serve a servant that is wise: and a man that is prudent and hath discipline will not murmur being rebuked, and the ignorant shall not be honoured. \x + \xo 10:28 \xt Prov. 17.\x*
\v 29 Extol not thyself in doing thy work, and linger not in the time of distress:
\v 30 better is he that worketh, and aboundeth in all things, than he that glorieth, and lacketh bread. \x + \xo 10:30 \xt Prov. 12.\x*
\v 31 Son in mildness keep thy soul, and give him honour according to his desert.
\v 32 Him that sinneth against his own soul who shall justify? And who shall honour him that dishonoureth his own soul?
\v 33 The poor man is glorified by his discipline and fear: & there is a man that is honoured for his substance.
\v 34 But he that is glorified in poverty, how much more in substance? And he that is glorified in substance, let him fear poverty.
\c 11
\p
\v 1 The wisdom of the humble shall exalt his head, & shall make him sit in the midst of great men. \f + \fr 11:1 \ft Awiseman humbling himself by penance, as Daniel did, or being unjustly humbled by others, as Ioseph was, shall be exalted by God.\f*
\v 2 Praise not a man in his beauty, neither despise a man by his look.
\v 3 The bee is small among fowls, and her fruit hath the beginning of sweetness.
\v 4 In apparel do not glory at any time, nor be extolled in the day of thine honour, because the works of the Highest only be marvelous, and his works are glorious, and secret, and not seen.
\v 5 Many tyrants have sit in the throne, and he whom no man would think hath worn the crown.
\v 6 Many mighty men have been greatly oppressed, and the glorious have been delivered into the hands of others.
\v 7 Before thou inquire, blame no man: and when thou hast inquired, chasten justly.
\v 8 Before thou hear, answer not a word, and in the midst of ancients add not to speak. \f + \fr 11:8 \ft Expect the end of another man's speech, before you begin to answer.\f* \f + \fr 11:8 \ft Expect also if any that is elder, or better able will answer first.\f*
\v 9 Strive not for that thing, which doth not molest thee: and consist not in the judgement of sinners. \x + \xo 11:9 \xt Deu. 13.\x*
\v 10 Son let not thy doings be in many things: and if thou be rich, thou shalt not be free from sin: for if thou pursue, thou shalt not attain: and if thou run before, thou shalt not escape.
\v 11 There is one that laboureth, and hasteneth, and is a sorrowful impious man, and so much the more he shall not abound.
\v 12 There is a lither man that wanteth recovery, more failing in strength, and abounding in poverty: \x + \xo 11:12 \xt Iob. 42.\x*
\v 13 and the eye of God hath respected him in good, and hath erected him from his low estate, and hath exalted his head: and many have marveled at him, and have honoured God.
\v 14 Good things and evil, life and death, poverty and honesty are of God.
\v 15 Wisdom and discipline, and the knowledge of the law are with God. Love, and the ways of good things are with him.
\v 16 Error & darkness are created with sinners: and they that rejoice in evils, wax old in evil. \f + \fr 11:16 \ft One punishment of sin is blindness of heart, especially where is no remorse of conscience.\f*
\v 17 The gift of God is permanent to the just, and his prospering shall have success for ever.
\v 18 There is that is enriched by doing sparingly, and this is the portion of his reward,
\v 19 in that he saith: I have found me rest, and now I will eat of my goods alone:
\v 20 and he knoweth not that time passeth, & death approacheth, and he must leave all to others, and shall die.
\v 21 Stand in thy covenant, and commune therein, and grow old in the work of thy commandments.
\v 22 Abide not in the works of sinners. But trust in God, and tarry in thy place.
\v 23 For it is easy in the eyes of God suddenly to enrich the poor man.
\v 24 The blessing of God hasteneth to the reward of the just, and in a swift hour his prospering fructifieth.
\v 25 Say not: What need I, and what good shall I have by this?
\v 26 Say not: I am sufficient for myself: and what shall I be made worse by this?
\v 27 In the day of good things be not unmindful of evils: and in the day of evils be not unmindful of good things: \f + \fr 11:27 \ft In prosperity is fear, and in adversity hope of change.\f*
\v 28 because it is easy before God in the day of death to reward every one according to his ways.
\v 29 The malice of an hour maketh oblivion of great voluptuousness, and in the end of a man in the disclosing of his works.
\v 30 Before death praise no man, because a man is known in his children.
\v 31 Bring not every man into thine house: for there be many trains of the deceitful man.
\v 32 For as the stomachs belch of stinking breaths, and as the partridge is brought in to the cage, and as the doe into the snare: so also the heart of the proud, and as a watch-man that seeth the fall of his neighbour.
\v 33 For turning good things into evil he lieth in wait, and on the elect he will lay a blot.
\v 34 For of one spark fire is increased, and of a deceitful man blood is increased: and a sinful man lieth in wait for blood.
\v 35 Take heed of thyself of the pestiferous person, for he forgeth evils: lest perhaps he bring upon thee derision for ever.
\v 36 Admit a stranger to thee, and he shall overthrow thee in an hurlwind, & shall make thee an alien from thine own.
\c 12
\p
\v 1 If thou wilt do good, know to whom thou doest it, and there shall be much thank in thy good deeds. \f + \fr 12:1 \ft It is rather cruelty than mercy to nourish a wicked man persisting in sin: for so he runneth still into more wickedness, and into eternal damnation:\f*
\v 2 Do good to the just, and thou shalt find great reward: and if not of him, assuredly of our Lord.
\v 3 For it is not well with him, that is ever occupied in evil things, and that giveth not alms: because the Highest both hateth sinners, and hath mercy on them that are penitent. \f + \fr 12:3 \ft but the penitent is to be comforted and assisted.\f*
\v 4 Give to the merciful, and receive not the sinner: both to the impious & to sinners he will repay vengeance, keeping them unto the day of vengeance.
\v 5 Give to the good, and receive not a sinner.
\v 6 Do good to the humble, and give not to the impious: prohibit to give him bread, lest therein he be mightier than thou:
\v 7 for thou shalt find double evils in all the good, whatsoever thou shalt do to him: because the Highest hateth sinners, and will repay vengeance to the impious.
\v 8 Afriend shall not be known in prosperity, and an enemy shall not be hid in adversity.
\v 9 In the prosperity of a man, his enemies are in sorrow, and in affliction a friend is known.
\v 10 Credit not thine enemy for ever: for as a brass pot his wickedness rusteth: \f + \fr 12:10 \ft Every one is bound to love his enemy of charity; but in prudence it behoveth not to credit him. According to our Saviour's rule: Be wise as serpents and simple as doves. Mat. 10.\f*
\v 11 and if humbling himself he go crouching, be advised in thy mind, and beware of him.
\v 12 Place him not by thee, neither let him sit on thy right hand, lest perhaps turning into thy place, he seek after thy seat: and at the last thou know my words, and be pricked in my sayings.
\v 13 Who will have pity upon the enchanter striking of a serpent, or of any that come near to beasts? So also he that keepeth company with a wicked man, and is wrapped in his sins.
\v 14 For one hour he will tarry with thee: but if thou decline, he will not abide it.
\v 15 In his lips the enemy speaketh sweetly, and in his heart he lieth in wait, that he may overthrow thee into the pit.
\v 16 In his eyes the enemy weepeth: and if he may find a time, he will not be satisfied with blood:
\v 17 and if evils happen to thee, thou shalt find him there first.
\v 18 In his eyes the enemy weepeth, and as it were helping thee, he will undermine thy feet.
\v 19 He will shake his head, and clap his hand, and whispering many things he will change his countenance.
\c 13
\p
\v 1 He that toucheth pitch, shall be defiled with it: and he that communicateth with the proud, shall put on pride. \x + \xo 13:1 \xt Deut. 7.\x*
\v 2 He shall take a burden upon him that communicateth with one more honourable than himself. And be not companion with one richer than thyself. \f + \fr 13:2 \ft He that converseth with a greater man than himself (except it be with virtuous) is forced often to suffer much, and to yield to many inconveniences.\f*
\v 3 What society shall the cauldron have with the earthen pot? For when they shall knock one against the other, it shall be broken.
\v 4 The rich man hath done unjustly, and he will fume: but the poor man being hurt will hold his peace.
\v 5 If thou give, he will take thee: and if thou have not, he will forsake thee.
\v 6 If thou have, he will live with thee, and will empty thee, and he will not be sorry for thee.
\v 7 If thou be necessary for him, he will supplant thee, and smiling will put thee in hope, telling thee good things, and will say: What wantest thou?
\v 8 And he will confound thee in his meats, till he empty thee twice & thrice, and at the last he will mock thee: and afterward seeing he will forsake thee, and will shake his head at thee.
\v 9 Humble thyself to God, and expect his hands.
\v 10 Take heed lest seduced into folly thou be humbled.
\v 11 Be not humble in thy wisdom, lest humbled thou be seduced into folly. \f + \fr 13:11 \ft Pusillanimity in a superior maketh him omit his duty, & commit errors, fearing to do that pertaineth to his office, & which his authority requireth.\f*
\v 12 Being called of the mightier, depart: for by this he will call thee the more.
\v 13 Be not importune, lest thou be rejected: & be not far from him, lest thou go into oblivion.
\v 14 Stay not to speak fellow-like with him: neither credit his many words. For by much talk he will prove thee, and smiling will examine thee of thy secrets.
\v 15 His cruel mind will keep thy words: and he will not spare for malice, and for bands.
\v 16 Take heed to thyself, and attend diligently to thine hearing: because thou walkest with thy subversion.
\v 17 But hearing those things see as it were in sleep, and thou shalt watch.
\v 18 Love God all thy life, and invocate him for thy salvation.
\v 19 Every beast loveth the like to it-self: so also every man the nearest to himself.
\v 20 All flesh will march with the like to it-self, & every man will associate himself to his like.
\v 21 If the wolf shall at any time communicate with the lamb, so the sinner with the just.
\v 22 What fellowship hath an holy man with a dog, or what part hath the rich with the poor?
\v 23 The wild ass in the desert is the lion's prey: so the poor are also the pastures of the rich.
\v 24 And as humility is abomination to the proud: so also the poor man is the execration of the rich.
\v 25 The rich man being moved is confirmed by his friends: but the humble when he is fallen, shall be thrust out even of his familiars.
\v 26 To the rich deceived there are many recoverers: he hath spoken proud words, and they have justified him.
\v 27 The humble was deceived, he moreover is rebuked also: he hath spoken wisely, and place was not given unto him.
\v 28 The rich man spake, and all held their peace, and they will carry his word even to the clouds. \f + \fr 13:28 \ft Acception of persons hindereth many good counsels: & promoteth many evil things.\f*
\v 29 The poor man spake and they say: Who is this? And if he stumble, they will overthrow him.
\v 30 Substance is good, to him that hath no sin in his conscience: and poverty is most wicked in the mouth of the impious.
\v 31 The heart of a man altereth his countenance, either into good, or into evil.
\v 32 The token of a good heart, and a good countenance thou shalt hardly find, and with labour.
\c 14
\p
\v 1 Blessed is the man that hath not offended in a word out of his mouth, and is not pricked with the sorrow of sin. \x + \xo 14:1 \xt Iac. 3.\x*
\v 2 Happy is he, that hath not had heaviness of his mind, and hath not fallen from his hope.
\v 3 Substance is without reason to the covetous man and niggard, and for the spiteful envious man to what purpose is gold?
\v 4 He that heapeth together from his heart unjustly, gathereth for others, and in his goods another will keep riot.
\v 5 He that is wicked to himself, to what other man will he be good? And he shall have no pleasure in his goods.
\v 6 He that envieth himself, nothing is worse than he, and this is the reward of his malice: \f + \fr 14:6 \ft He that cannot afford nourishment to his own body by such means as he hath, sinneth against God, abusing his benefits against himself whom he unjustly afflicteth, and against his neighbour whom he scandalizeth.\f*
\v 7 and if he do good, he doth it ignorantly, and not willing: and at the last he manifesteth his malice.
\v 8 The eye of the envious is wicked, and turneth away his face, and despiseth his own soul.
\v 9 The eye of the covetous man insatiable in a portion of iniquity, will not be satisfied till he consume his own soul withering it. \x + \xo 14:9 \xt Prov. 27. v. 20.\x*
\v 10 An evil eye is towards evil things: & he shall have his fill of bread, needy & in heaviness shall he be at his table.
\v 11 Son if thou have it, do good to thyself, and offer to God worthy oblations.
\v 12 Be mindful that death slacked not, and that the covenant of hell hath been shewed thee: for the covenant of this world shall die the death. \f + \fr 14:12 \ft In the old testament all descended into some part of hell.\f*
\v 13 Before death do good to thy friend, and according to thine ability stretching out thy hand, give to the poor.
\v 14 Be not defrauded of thy good day, and let not a little portion of a good gift over-pass thee.
\v 15 Shalt thou not leave to others thy sorrows, & labours in the division of the lot?
\v 16 Give and take, and justify thy soul.
\v 17 Before thy death work justice: for in hell there cannot meat be found.
\v 18 All flesh shall wax old as grass, and as the leaf fructifying on a green tree. \x + \xo 14:18 \xt Isa. 40. v. 7.\x*
\v 19 Some grow, and some are shaken off: so the generation of flesh and blood, one is ended, and another is born.
\v 20 All corruptible work shall fail in the end: and he that worketh it shall go therewith.
\v 21 And every excellent work shall be justified: and he that worketh it, shall be honoured therein. \f + \fr 14:21 \ft There shall be particular reward of every good work.\f*
\v 22 Blessed is the man that shall continue in wisdom, and that shall meditate in his justice, and in understanding shall consider the providence of God.
\v 23 He that considereth her ways in his heart, and hath understanding in her secrets, going after her as a searcher, and consisting in her ways:
\v 24 He that looketh through her windows, and heareth in her gates:
\v 25 He that resteth by her house, & in her walls fastening a stake will set up his cottage beside her hands: and good things shall rest in his cottage for ever.
\v 26 He shall set his children under her covering, and shall abide under her boughs:
\v 27 he shall be protected under her covering from the heat, and shall rest in her glory.
\c 15
\p
\v 1 He that feareth God, shall do good things, and he that hath justice shall apprehend her, \f + \fr 15:1 \ft Whosoever shall resolve with himself to live justly, shall be sure to have grace, for God preventeth our weakness and so continueth to help all that accept his grace.\f*
\v 2 and she will meet him as an honourable mother, & a wife from virginity she will receive him.
\v 3 She shall feed him with the bread of life and understanding, and give him the water of wholesome wisdom to drink: and she shall be made sure in him, and he shall not be bowed:
\v 4 and she shall hold him fast, and he shall not be confounded: and she shall exalt him before his neighbours,
\v 5 and in the midst of the Church she shall open his mouth, and shall fill him with the spirit of wisdom and understanding, and shall clothe him with a stole of glory.
\v 6 Joy & exultation she shall heap upon him, & shall make him inherit an everlasting name.
\v 7 Foolish men shall not apprehend her, & wise men shall meet her, foolish men shall not see her: for she is far from pride and deceit.
\v 8 Lying men shall not be mindful of her: and true men shall be found in her, and shall have success, even to the beholding of God.
\v 9 Praise is not comely in the mouth of a sinner: \f + \fr 15:9 \ft He doth injury to God, & to his word, that preacheth well and liveth evil.\f*
\v 10 because wisdom proceeded from God. For praise shall be with the wisdom of God, & shall abound in a faithful mouth, & the dominatour will give praise to it.
\v 11 Say not: It is by God, that she is absent: for do not thou the things that he hateth. \f + \fr 15:11 \ft Beza saith God ordained Adam's fall, but to a good end: and that God justly decreed that which men unjustly have done. in refut. 2. calumniæ, ad Castel. But this holy Scripture teacheth the contrary, that God gave man both free-will, and sufficient grace, that he might if he would have kept his precepts. The same is also clearly taught. Deut. 7. 11. 30. and other places.\f*
\v 12 Say not: He hath made me err: for impious men are not necessary for him.
\v 13 Our Lord hateth all abomination of error, and it shall not be amiable to them, that fear him.
\v 14 God from the beginning made man, and left him in the hand of his own counsel. \x + \xo 15:14 \xt Gen. 2.\x*
\v 15 He added his commandments and precepts.
\v 16 If thou will keep the commandment, and keep acceptable fidelity for ever, they shall preserve thee. \x + \xo 15:16 \xt Mat. 19. v. 17.\x*
\v 17 He hath set before thee water and fire: to which thou wilt, stretch forth thine hand.
\v 18 Before man there is life and death, good and evil: what pleaseth him shall be given him: \x + \xo 15:18 \xt Ier. 2. v. 8.\x*
\v 19 Because the wisdom of God is much, and he is strong in might, seeing all men without intermission.
\v 20 The eyes of our Lord are towards them that fear him, and he knoweth all the work of man.
\v 21 He hath commanded no man to do impiously, and he hath given no man space to sin:
\v 22 for he desireth not a multitude of faithless and unprofitable children.
\c 16
\p
his mercy on the good. 14. Works of mercy merit great \add reward. 15. Nothing is hid from God, 20. but many things from men.\add*
\v 1 Rejoice not in impious children, if they be multiplied: neither be delighted upon them, if the fear of God be not in them.
\v 2 Credit not their life, and respect not their labours.
\v 3 For better is one fearing God, than a thousand impious children.
\v 4 And it is more profitable to die without children, rather than to leave impious children.
\v 5 By one wise a country shall be inhabited, and the tribe of the impious shall be made desolate.
\v 6 Many such things hath mine eye seen, and mine ear hath heard things of more force than these.
\v 7 In the synagogue of sinners a fire shall flame, and in an incredulous nation wrath shall wax hot. \f + \fr 16:7 \ft Fire of concupiscence, if it be not overcome in this life, will procure the fire of God's wrath, which shall never be extinguished.\f*
\v 8 The old giants did not obtain for their sins, who were destroyed trusting to their own strength: \x + \xo 16:8 \xt Gen. 6.\x*
\v 9 and he spared not the peregrination of Lot, and he detested them for the pride of their word.
\v 10 He had not pity on them, destroying the whole nation, and extolling themselves in their sins.
\v 11 And as the six hundred thousand foot men, which were gathered together in the hardness of their heart: and if one had been stiff necked, it is marvel if he had been unpunished. \x + \xo 16:11 \xt Num. 26.\x*
\v 12 For there is mercy and wrath with him. Mighty exoration, & pouring out wrath:
\v 13 according to his mercy, so his chastisement judgeth a man according to his works.
\v 14 The sinner shall not escape in robbery, and the sufferance of him that doth mercy shall not slack.
\v 15 All mercy shall make a place to every man according to the merit of his works, & according to the understanding of his peregrination.
\v 16 Say not: I shall be hid from God, and from on high who shall remember me?
\v 17 In a great people I shall not be known: for what is my soul among so innumerable creatures?
\v 18 Behold heaven, and the heavens of heavens, the depth, and all the earth, & the things that are in them, in his sight shall be moved,
\v 19 the mountains together, and the little hills, & the foundations of the earth: & when God shall behold them, they shall be shaken with trembling.
\v 20 And in all these things the heart is senseless: and every heart is understood of him:
\v 21 and his ways who doth understand, and the storm, which neither the eye of man shall see?
\v 22 For many of his works are in secrets: but the works of his justice who shall declare? Or who shall sustain? For the testament is far from some, and the examination of all is in consummation.
\v 23 He that is less of heart, thinketh vain things: and the unwise, and erring man, thinketh foolish things.
\v 24 Hear me my son, and learn the discipline of understanding, and attend to my words in thy heart,
\v 25 and I will speak discipline in equity, and will search to declare wisdom: and to my words attend in thy heart, and I speak in equity of spirit the virtues, that God hath put upon his works from the beginning, and in truth I shew forth his knowledge.
\v 26 In the judgement of God are his works from the beginning, and from the institution of them he distinguished their parts, and their beginnings in their nations.
\v 27 He adorned their works for ever, neither have they hungered, nor laboured, and they have not ceased from their works.
\v 28 Every one shall not vex his neighbour for ever.
\v 29 Be not incredulous to his word.
\v 30 After this God looked upon the earth, & filled it with his good things.
\v 31 And the soul of every living thing shall shew before the face thereof, and into it again is their return. \f + \fr 16:31 \ft Reasonable souls (if they follow reason) and all sensible souls do (in their manner) praise the providence of God, in using all creatures to that end for which they were created.\f*
\c 17
\p
\v 1 God created man of the earth, and after his own image he made him.
\v 2 And again he turned him into it, and conformable to himself clothed him with strength. \f + \fr 17:2 \ft Man at first received original justice, by losing whereof we all fell into original sin.\f*
\v 3 He gave him a number of days and time, and gave him power of those things that are upon the earth.
\v 4 He put his fear over all flesh, and he had dominion of beasts and fowls.
\v 5 He created of him an helper like to himself: he gave them counsel, and tongue, and eyes, & ears, and heart to devise: and he filled them with the discipline of understanding.
\v 6 He created in them the knowledge of the spirit, he filled their heart with understanding, and evil and good he shewed them.
\v 7 He set his eye upon their hearts to shew them the great things of his works:
\v 8 that they might praise the name of sanctification: & glory in his marvelous works, that they might declare the glorious things of his works.
\v 9 He added discipline unto them, and made them inherit the law of life. \f + \fr 17:9 \ft God gave a precept to man to be observed for exercise of his obedience, & so to be rewarded, and under pain of punishment if he transgressed. Gen. 2.\f*
\v 10 He made an everlasting testament with them, & he shewed them justice and his judgements.
\v 11 And their eye saw the glorious things of his honour, & their ears heard the honour of his voice, and he said to them: Beware of every unjust thing.
\v 12 And he gave them commandment every one concerning his neighbour.
\v 13 Their ways are before him always, they are not hid from his eyes.
\v 14 Over every nation he appointed a ruler.
\v 15 And Israel was made the manifest portion of God. \x + \xo 17:15 \xt Rom. 13.\x*
\v 16 And all their works as the sun in the sight of God: and his eyes without intermission looking on their ways.
\v 17 The testaments were not hid by their iniquity, and all their iniquities are in the sight of God.
\v 18 The alms of a man is as a seal with him, and shall preserve the grace of a man as the apple of the eye:
\v 19 And afterward he shall arise, and shall render them reward, to every one upon their head, and shall turn into the inner parts of the earth.
\v 20 But to the penitent he hath given the way of justice, and he hath confirmed them that fail to sustain, and hath appointed to them the lot of truth.
\v 21 Turn to our Lord, and forsake thy sins:
\v 22 pray before the face of our Lord, and diminish offences.
\v 23 Return to our Lord, & turn away from thine injustice, and hate exceedingly abomination:
\v 24 and know the justices and judgments of God, and stand in the lot of thy purpose, and of prayer of the most high God. \f + \fr 17:24 \ft Perseverance in virtue to the end is necessary, which none can merit.\f* \f + \fr 17:24 \ft But must still pray for it.\f*
\v 25 Go into the parts of the holy world, with the living, and them that give praise to God.
\v 26 Tarry not in the error of the impious, before death confess. From the dead as nothing, confession perisheth.
\v 27 Thou shalt confess living, alive and in health thou shalt confess, and shalt praise God, and shalt glory in his mercies.
\v 28 How great is the mercy of our Lord, and his propitiation to them that turn to him!
\v 29 For all things cannot be in men, because the son of man is not immortal, and they have delighted in the vanity of malice.
\v 30 What is brighter than the sun? & it shall fail. Or what more wicked than that which flesh and blood hath invented? And this shall be reproved.
\v 31 He beholdeth the power of the height of heaven: and all men be earth and ashes.
\c 18
\p
\v 1 He that liveth for ever, created all things together. God only shall be justified, and remaineth an invincible King for ever. \f + \fr 18:1 \ft All creatures according to their substantial form in general, were created together, though they were afterwards formed in particular kinds, as they are distinctly recited in Genesis, with the order & ornaments of the world. S. Aug. li. 4. c. 33. & 34. de Gen. ad litter. Where he expressly affirmeth that this Scripture was written by inspiration of the same spirit of truth, whereby Genesis was written.\f*
\v 2 Who is sufficient to declare his works?
\v 3 For who shall search out his glorious things?
\v 4 and who shall shew forth the power of his greatness? Or who shall add to declare his mercy?
\v 5 It is not possible to diminish, nor add, neither is it possible to find the glorious works of God:
\v 6 When a man, shall have done, then shall he begin: and when he shall rest, he shall work.
\v 7 What is man: and what is his grace? And what is his good, or what his evil?
\v 8 The number of the days of men at the most an hundred years: as drops of the water of the sea they are reputed: and as the gravel stone of the sand, so a few years in the day of eternity. \x + \xo 18:8 \xt Psa. 89. v. 10.\x*
\v 9 For this cause God is patient toward them, and poureth out his mercy upon them.
\v 10 He hath seen the presumption of their heart that it is naught, and hath known their subversion that it is evil.
\v 11 Therefore hath he fulfilled his propitiation toward them, and hath shewed them the way of equity.
\v 12 Man's compassion is touching his neighbour: but the mercy of God is upon all flesh.
\v 13 He that hath mercy, teacheth and instructeth, as a pastor his flock.
\v 14 He hath mercy on him that receiveth the doctrine of compassion, and he that hasteneth in his judgements.
\v 15 Son in good deeds give no blame, & in every gift give not the sadness of an evil word.
\v 16 Shall not the dew cool heat? So also a word better than a gift.
\v 17 Is not a word above a good gift? But both are with a justified man.
\v 18 Afool will upbraid bitterly: and the gift of one untaught maketh the eyes to dry away.
\v 19 Before judgment prepare thee justice, and before thou speak learn.
\v 20 Before sickness take medicine, and before judgement examine thyself, and in the sight of God thou shalt find propitiation. \x + \xo 18:20 \xt 1. Cor. 11.\x*
\v 21 Before sickness humble thyself, and in time of infirmity shew thy conversation.
\v 22 Be not hindered to pray always, & fear not to be justified even to death, because the reward of God abideth for ever.
\v 23 Before prayer prepare thy soul: and be not as a man that tempteth God.
\v 24 Remember the wrath in the day of consummation, and the time of reward in conversation of the face.
\v 25 Remember poverty in the time of aboundance, & the necessities of poverty in the day of riches.
\v 26 From morning unto evening time shall be changed, & all these are sown in the eyes of God.
\v 27 Awise man in all things will fear, and in the days of offences will beware of sloth.
\v 28 Every subtile man knoweth wisdom, and to him that findeth her he will give praise.
\v 29 The wise in words, and they also have done wisely: and have understood truth and justice, and have rained proverbs & judgments.
\v 30 Go not after thy concupiscences, and turn away from thy will.
\v 31 If thou give to thy soul her concupiscences, she will make thee a joy to thy enemies.
\v 32 Be not delighted in multitudes, nor in few: for their concertation is continual.
\v 33 Be not poor in contention of borrowing, and thou hast nothing in thy purse: for thou shalt be envious to thine own life.
\c 19
\p
\v 1 Aworkman that is a drunkard shall not be rich: and he that contemneth small things, shall fall by little and little. \f + \fr 19:1 \ft The best remedy against great sins is to avoid small ones, and not to contemn the least, but diligently to amend all.\f*
\v 2 Wine and women make wisemen to apostatate, and shall reprove the prudent: \x + \xo 19:2 \xt 3. Reg. 11.\x*
\v 3 and he that joineth himself to harlots, shall be naught. Rottenness and worms shall inherit him, and he shall be lifted up for a greater example, and his life shall be taken out of the number.
\v 4 He that giveth credit quickly, is light of heart, and shall be lessened: and he shall moreover be counted one that sinneth against his own soul. \x + \xo 19:4 \xt Ios. 22.\x*
\v 5 He that rejoiceth in iniquity, shall be reprehended, and he that hateth chastisement shall be diminished of life: and he that hateth babbling, extinguisheth malice.
\v 6 He that sinneth against his own soul, shall repent: and he that is delighted in naughtiness, shall be reprehended.
\v 7 Iterate not a wicked and hard word, and thou shalt not be lessened.
\v 8 To friend and foe tell not thy mind: and if thou have sin disclose it not. \f + \fr 19:8 \ft That this document pertaineth to common conversation with worldly men, appeareth by the next verse. But to reveal secret sins to a spiritual father in sacramental confession, is necessary, wholesome, and secure. It is also very commendable and most lawful in holy religious Societies, where they willingly for their own spiritual good submit themselves to such a godly rule.\f*
\v 9 For he will hear thee, and will watch thee, and as it were defending the sin he will hate thee, and so will he be present with thee always.
\v 10 Hast thou heard a word against thy neighbour? Let it die together in thee, trusting that it will not burst thee.
\v 11 At the presence of a word the fool travaileth, as the groaning of the childbirth of an infant.
\v 12 An arrow stickt in the thigh of flesh: so is a word in the heart of a fool.
\v 13 Rebuke a friend, lest perhaps he hath not understood, and say: I did it not: or if he did it, that he do it not again. \x + \xo 19:13 \xt Levit. 19. Mat. 18.\x*
\v 14 Rebuke thy neighbour, lest perhaps he said it not: and if he said it, lest perhaps he iterate it.
\v 15 Rebuke thy friend: for there is often a fault committed.
\v 16 And believe not every word. There is that offendeth with the tongue, but not from his heart.
\v 17 For who is there that hath not offended in his tongue? Rebuke thy neighbour before thou threaten. \x + \xo 19:17 \xt Iac. 3.\x*
\v 18 And give place to the fear of the Highest: because the fear of God is all wisdom, and to fear God is in it, & the disposition of the law is in all wisdom.
\v 19 And the discipline of wickedness is not wisdom: and the cogitation of sinners is not prudence.
\v 20 There is wickedness, and in it execration: and there is a fool that hath less wisdom.
\v 21 Better is a man that hath less wisdom and lacketh understanding, in fear, than he that aboundeth in understanding and transgresseth the law of the Highest.
\v 22 There is an assured subtility, & the same wicked.
\v 23 And there is that uttereth an exact word telling the truth. There is that wickedly humbleth himself, and his inner parts be full of deceit: \f + \fr 19:23 \ft False pretence of piety is hypocrisy.\f*
\v 24 and there is a just man that submitteth himself overmuch of great humility: and there is a just one that boweth his face, and feigneth himself not to see that which is unknown: \f + \fr 19:24 \ft And in a Superior, to open his own secret fault to his subjects, is pusillanimity.\f* \f + \fr 19:24 \ft Discretion avoideth both: by concealing and revealing faults as reason directeth and justice requireth.\f*
\v 25 and if he be forbidden to sin for imbecility of power, if he shall find a time to do evil, he will do evil.
\v 26 Aman is known by the sight, and a wiseman is known by the shew of his face.
\v 27 The clothing of the body, and the laughing of the teeth, and the going of the man tell of him.
\v 28 There is a lying chastisement in the anger of a contumelious person: and there is a judgement, that is not allowed to be good: and there is that holdeth his peace, and he is wise.
\c 20
\p
\v 1 How good a thing is it to rebuke, rather than to be angry, and not to hinder him that confesseth in prayer!
\v 2 The concupiscence of an eunuch shall deflower a young-maid:
\v 3 so he that by violence doth unjust judgement. \x + \xo 20:3 \xt Eccle. 3.\x*
\v 4 How good a thing is it being rebuked to shew repentance! For so thou shalt avoid willful sin. \f + \fr 20:4 \ft He that taketh reprehension in good part when he is faulty meriteth pardon, and when he is not faulty he satisfieth for his other sins and meriteth reward.\f*
\v 5 There is that holdeth his peace, which is found wise: and there is that is odious, he which is malapert to speak.
\v 6 There is that holdeth his peace having not understanding to speak: and there is that holdeth his peace, knowing the time of fit opportunity.
\v 7 Awise man will hold his peace until a time: but a wanton, and the unwise will not observe time.
\v 8 He that useth many words, shall hurt his own soul: & he that taketh authority to himself unjustly, shall be hated.
\v 9 There is proceeding in evils to a man without discipline, and there is finding to loss.
\v 10 There is a gift, that is not profitable: and there is a gift, the reward whereof is double.
\v 11 There is debasing because of glory: and there is that from humility shall lift up the head.
\v 12 There is that redeemeth many things for a small price, and restoreth the same seven-fold.
\v 13 Aman wise in words shall make himself beloved: but the graces of fools shall be poured out.
\v 14 The gift of the unwise shall not be profitable for thee: for his eyes are seven-fold. \f + \fr 20:14 \ft His intention is full of guile that flattereth by shew of love and of praise, but he will detract so much the more, & in the end reproach when he may get probable advantage against thee.\f*
\v 15 He will give few things, and upbraid many: and the opening of his mouth is an inflammation.
\v 16 Today a man lendeth, and tomorrow he asketh it again: such a man is odious.
\v 17 Afool shall have no friend, and there shall be not thank to his goods.
\v 18 For they that eat his bread, are of a false tongue. How often, and how many will laugh him to scorn?
\v 19 For he doth not distribute with right understanding, that which was to be had: in like manner also that which was not to be had.
\v 20 The slipping of a false tongue, as he that falleth on the pavement: so the falls of the evil shall come hastily.
\v 21 Aman without grace is as a vain fable, it shall be continual in the mouth of them that are without discipline.
\v 22 Aparable out of a fool's mouth shall be rejected: for he doth not speak it in his time.
\v 23 There is that is forbid to sin for poverty, and in his rest he shall be pricked.
\v 24 There is that will destroy his soul for shamefastness, and by an unwise person he will destroy it: and by acception of person he will destroy himself.
\v 25 There is that for shamefastness promiseth to his friend, and hath gotten an enemy of him for naught.
\v 26 Lying is a wicked reproach in a man, and in the mouth of men without discipline it shall be continually.
\v 27 Better is a thief, than the continual custom of a lying man, but both shall inherit perdition.
\v 28 The manners of lying men are without honour: and their confusion is with them without intermission.
\v 29 Awise man in his words shall utter himself, and a prudent man shall please great persons.
\v 30 He that tilleth his land, shall make an high heap of corn: and who so worketh justice, he shall be exalted: and he that pleaseth great men, shall avoid iniquity. \x + \xo 20:30 \xt Prov. 12.\x*
\v 31 Presents & gifts blind the eyes of judges, and as one dumb in the mouth turneth away their chastisements. \x + \xo 20:31 \xt Exo. 23. Deu. 16.\x*
\v 32 Wisdom hid, and treasure not seen: what profit is there in both? \f + \fr 20:32 \ft Wisdom is to be shewed in words and deeds when it may profit others.\f*
\v 33 Better is he that concealeth his foolishness, than the man that hideth his wisdom. \f + \fr 20:33 \ft To conceal faults, so they be amended, is most convenient.\f*
\c 21
\p
\v 1 Son hast thou sinned? Do so no more: but for the old also pray that they may be forgiven thee.
\v 2 As from the face of a serpent fly from sins: and if thou approach to them they will receive thee. \f + \fr 21:2 \ft As a serpent deceitfully approacheth & stingeth the body, so all sins inveigle and hurt the soul.\f*
\v 3 The teeth of a lion the teeth thereof, killing the souls of men.
\v 4 All iniquity is as a two-edged sword, there is no remedy for the wound thereof.
\v 5 Brawling and injuries shall bring the substance to nothing: and the house that is very rich, shall be made nothing by pride: so the substance of the proud shall be rooted out.
\v 6 The prayer of the poor out of the mouth shall come to his ears, and judgement shall come for him speedily.
\v 7 He that hateth chastisement, is the trace of a sinner: and he that feareth God, will turn to his own heart. \f + \fr 21:7 \ft It is a sign that he is guilty, who contemneth friendly admonition.\f* \f + \fr 21:7 \ft He that truly feareth God will diligently examine his own acts & defects when he is warned.\f*
\v 8 The mighty in a bold tongue is known a far off, and a wiseman knoweth himself to fall by him.
\v 9 He that buildeth his house at other men's charges, is as he that gathereth his stones in the winter. \f + \fr 21:9 \ft As walls of stone built in the frost, so riches or good name unjustly gotten will not continue long.\f*
\v 10 The synagogue of sinners is as tow gathered together, and their consummation a flame of fire.
\v 11 The way of sinners is paved with stones, & in their end, hell, & darkness, and pains.
\v 12 He that keepeth justice, shall contain the understanding thereof.
\v 13 The consummation of the fear of God wisdom and understanding.
\v 14 He shall not be taught, that is not wise in good.
\v 15 But there is wisdom that aboundeth in evil: and there is no understanding where bitterness is.
\v 16 The knowledge of the wise shall abound as an inundation, and his counsel is permanent as a fountain of life.
\v 17 The heart of a fool is as a broken vessel, and all wisdom it shall not hold.
\v 18 Aman of knowledge will praise what soever wise word he shall hear, and will apply it to himself: the riotous man hath heard it, and it shall displease him, and he will cast it behind his back.
\v 19 The narration of a fool is as a burden in the way: for in the lips of the wise shall grace be found. \f + \fr 21:19 \ft Senseless or bad talk is tedious to all good men.\f* \f + \fr 21:19 \ft Words that may edify are grateful to all godly ears.\f*
\v 20 The mouth of the prudent is sought in the Church, and they will think upon his words in their hearts.
\v 21 As a house destroyed, so is wisdom to a fool: & the knowledge of the unwise inexplicable words.
\v 22 Fetters on the feet, doctrine to a fool, and as manacles upon the right hand.
\v 23 Afool in laughter exalteth his voice, but a wise man will scarce laugh secretly.
\v 24 Doctrine to the prudent is a golden ornament, and as it were a bracelet on the right arm.
\v 25 The foot of a fool goeth easily into his neighbour's house: & a cunning man will be abashed at the person of the mighty.
\v 26 Afool will look from the window into the house: but he nurtured will stand without.
\v 27 It is the folly of a man to harken by the door: and a wiseman will be grieved with the contumely.
\v 28 The lips of the unwise shall tell foolish things: but the words of the wise shall be pondered in balance.
\v 29 The heart of fools is in their mouth: and the mouth of wisemen is in their heart.
\v 30 Whilst the impious curseth the devil, he curseth his own soul. \f + \fr 21:30 \ft Wicked men condemning the devil or any other wicked, do indeed condemn themselves. And to them agreeth that sentence of our Saviour: By thine own mouth I judge thee, naughty servant. Luc. 19.\f*
\v 31 The whisperer shall defile his soul, and shall be hated in all: and he that shall abide with him, shall be odious: the still man and wise shall be honoured.
\c 22
\p
\v 1 The sluggard is stoned with a dirty stone, & all men will speak of his disgrace. \f + \fr 22:1 \ft Contempt & ignominy is the worldly punishment of the slothful, besides his eternal damnation at the day of judgement. Mat. 25. v. 30.\f*
\v 2 The sluggard is stoned with the dung of oxen: and every one that shall touch him, will shake his hands.
\v 3 The confusion of the father is of a son without discipline: and the daughter shall be made of less account.
\v 4 Awise daughter is an inheritance to her husband: for she that confoundeth, is made a contumely to her father.
\v 5 She that is bold shameth father and husband, and shall not be inferior to the impious: but of them both she shall be dishonoured.
\v 6 Music in mourning is a tale out of time: scourges and doctrine are at all time wisdom.
\v 7 He that teacheth a fool, is as he that glueth together a pot-sherd.
\v 8 He that telleth a word to him that heareth not, is as he that raiseth up a man sleeping out of an heavy sleep.
\v 9 He speaketh with him that sleepeth, which uttereth wisdom to a fool: and in the end of the narration he saith: Who is this?
\v 10 Weep upon the dead, for his light hath failed: and weep upon a fool, for he faileth in understanding. \f + \fr 22:10 \ft In this and other places is not understood a fool that by defect of natural wit is ignorant, or an idiot, but he that is void of grace, full of malice, and wickedness.\f*
\v 11 Weep a little upon the dead, because he is at rest.
\v 12 For the wicked life of the very wicked, above the death of a fool. \f + \fr 22:12 \ft For the wicked life of such a one is worse than his death. v. 12.\f*
\v 13 The mourning of the dead is seven days: but of a fool and of the impious, all the days of their life. \x + \xo 22:13 \xt Gen. 50. Pro. 27.\x*
\v 14 Speak not much with a fool, and go not with the unwise.
\v 15 Keep thyself from him, that thou have no molestation, and thou shalt not be defiled with his sin.
\v 16 Turn aside from him, and thou shalt find rest, and shall not be wearied with his folly.
\v 17 What shall be heavier than lead? And what other name hath it but fool?
\v 18 It is easier to bear sand and salt, and a mass of iron, than an unwise man, and a fool, and impious. \x + \xo 22:18 \xt Pro. 27.\x*
\v 19 Aframe of wood bound together in the foundation of a building, shall not be dissolved: so also the heart confirmed in the cogitation of counsel.
\v 20 The cogitation of the wise at all time, yea by fear shall not be depraved.
\v 21 As stakes in high places, and plasterings laid without cost, shall not abide against the face of the wind:
\v 22 so also a fearful heart in the cogitation of a fool shall not resist against the violence of fear.
\v 23 As a trembling heart in the cogitation of a fool, all time will not fear, so also he that continueth always in the precepts of God.
\v 24 He that pricketh the eye, bringeth forth tears: and he that pricketh the heart, bringeth forth feeling.
\v 25 He that casteth a stone at fowls, and shall throw them down: so he that speaketh reproachfully to his friend, dissolveth friendship.
\v 26 Although thou drawest a sword at a friend, despair not: for there is returning to a friend. \f + \fr 22:26 \ft Atrue friend will not be lost for temporal damage nor danger.\f*
\v 27 If thou open a sad mouth, fear not: for there is agreement: except taunt, and reproach, and pride, and revealing of secret, and a treacherous wound: in all these things a friend will fly away. \f + \fr 22:27 \ft But the vices of derision, reproach, and the like violate all friendship with wise and good men.\f*
\v 28 Possess fidelity with a friend in his poverty, that in his goods also thou mayst rejoice.
\v 29 In the time of his tribulation continue faithful to him, that in his inheritance also thou mayst be heir with him.
\v 30 Before the fire the vapour of the chimney, and the smoke of the fire riseth on high: so also before blood evil words, and contumelies, & threats.
\v 31 I will not be ashamed to salute a friend, from his face I will not hide myself: and if there chance evils to me by him, I will bear it.
\v 32 Every one that shall hear, will beware of him.
\v 33 Who will give a guard to my mouth, and a sure seal upon my lips, that I fall not by them, and my tongue destroy me? \x + \xo 22:33 \xt Ps. 140.\x*
\c 23
\p
\v 1 O Lord father, and dominatour of my life, leave me not in their counsel: nor suffer me to fall in them. \f + \fr 23:1 \ft Man being weak and the enemy subtle & strong, he is not able to resist tentations without God's special grace, for which the wiseman therefore prayeth, instructing all by his example to do the same.\f*
\v 2 Who layeth on stripes in my cogitation, and in my heart the doctrine of wisdom, and in their ignorances they spare me not, and their offences appear not,
\v 3 and my ignorances increase not, and my offences be multiplied, and my sins abound, and I fall in the sight of mine adversaries, & mine enemy rejoice?
\v 4 O Lord father, and God of my life, leave me not in their cogitation.
\v 5 Haughtiness of mine eyes give me not, and all desire turn away from me.
\v 6 Take from me the concupiscences of the belly, and let not the concupiscences of copulation take hold of me, and give me not over to a shameless and foolish mind.
\v 7 O children hear the doctrine of the mouth: and he that will keep it, shall not perish by his lips, nor be scandalized in most wicked works. \f + \fr 23:7 \ft Precepts how to govern the mouth, and tongue.\f*
\v 8 Asinner is taught in his vanity, and the proud and the evil speaker shall be scandalized in them.
\v 9 Let not thy mouth be accustomed to swearing: for there be many falls in it. \f + \fr 23:9 \ft Against rash, untrue, & unlawful swearing. Iere. 4.\f* \x + \xo 23:9 \xt Mat. 5.\x*
\v 10 But let not the naming of God be usual in thy mouth, and meddle not with the names of Saints, because thou shalt not scape free from them.
\v 11 For as a servant daily examined, lacketh not the mark thereof: so every one that sweareth, and nameth, shall not be wholly purged from sin.
\v 12 Aman that sweareth much shall be filled with iniquity, and plague shall not depart from his house.
\v 13 And if he frustrate it, his sin shall be upon him: and if he dissemble, he offendeth double:
\v 14 and if he swear in vain, he shall not be justified: for his house shall be filled with retribution.
\v 15 There is another contrary speech, also to death, be it not found in the inheritance of Jacob. \f + \fr 23:15 \ft In oaths God is called to witness as he that cannot lie, but blasphemy attributeth that to God which pertaineth not to him or attributeth to some creature that which only belongeth to God, and so is a contrary sin to unlawful swearing. Both are mortal sins.\f*
\v 16 For of the merciful all those things shall be taken away, and they will not wallow in sins.
\v 17 Let not thy mouth be accustomed to unuttered speech: for there is in it a word of sin. \f + \fr 23:17 \ft Admonition against sins, of the tongue.\f*
\v 18 Remember thy father and thy mother, for thou sittest in the midst of great men: \f + \fr 23:18 \ft Reproach to parents, and other neighbours.\f*
\v 19 lest perhaps God forget thee in their sight, & being besotted with thy daily custom, thou suffer reproach, & hadst better not have been born, and curse the day of thy nativity.
\v 20 Aman accustomed to the words of reproach, will not be instructed in all his days.
\v 21 Two sorts abound in sins, and the third bringeth wrath and perdition.
\v 22 An hot soul as a burning fire will not be quenched, till it swallow somewhat. \f + \fr 23:22 \ft Against covetousness.\f*
\v 23 and a wicked man in the mouth of his flesh will not cease till he kindle a fire.
\v 24 To a man that is a fornicator all bread is sweet, he will not be weary transgressing unto the end. \f + \fr 23:24 \ft Fornication.\f*
\v 25 Every man that passeth beyond his own bed, contemning against his own soul, and saying: Who seeth me? \f + \fr 23:25 \ft Adultery.\f*
\v 26 Darkness compasseth me, and the walls cover me, and no man beholdeth me: whom do I fear? The Highest will not be mindful of my sins. \x + \xo 23:26 \xt Isa. 26.\x*
\v 27 And he understandeth not that his eye seeth all things, for that such fear of man expelleth from him the fear of God, & the eyes of men fearing him:
\v 28 and he knoweth not that the eyes of our Lord are much more brighter than the sun, beholding round about all the ways of man, and the bottom of the depth, and the hearts of men, looking into the hidden parts.
\v 29 For all things were known unto our Lord God, before they were created: so also after it is perfected he beholdeth all things.
\v 30 Revenge shall be taken on this man in the streets of the city, and as an horse-colt he shall be chased: and where he expected not, he shall be apprehended.
\v 31 And he shall be in dishonour with all men, for that he understood not the fear of our Lord.
\v 32 So every woman also that forsaketh her husband, & getteth inheritance by marriage of another.
\v 33 For first she hath been unfaithful in the law of the Highest: and secondly she hath sinned against her husband: thirdly she hath fornicated in adultery, and hath gotten her children of another man.
\v 34 This woman shall be brought into the Church, and upon her children there shall be examination.
\v 35 Her children shall not take root, & her boughs shall not yield fruit.
\v 36 She shall leave her memory to be cursed, and her dishonour shall not be wiped out.
\v 37 And they that are left shall know, that nothing is better than the fear of God: and nothing sweeter, than to have regard to the commandments of our Lord.
\v 38 It is great glory to follow our Lord: for length of days shall be taken of him.
\c 24
\p
\v 1 Wisdom shall praise her soul, & shall be honoured in God, and shall glory in the midst of her people, \f + \fr 24:1 \ft Divine wisdom, the Second Person of the B. Trinity, begotten, not created, praiseth itself. According to the phrase of speech. Iere. 51. v. 14. The Lord of hosts hath sworn by his soul, that is, by himself.\f*
\v 2 and shall open her mouth in the churches of the Highest, and shall glory in the sight of his power,
\v 3 and in the midst of her people she shall be exalted, and in the holy assembly she shall be admired,
\v 4 and in the multitude of the elect she shall have praise, and among the blessed she shall be blessed, saying:
\v 5 I came forth from the mouth of the Highest, the first begotten before all creatures.
\v 6 I made that in the heavens, there should rise light that faileth not, and as a cloud I covered all the earth.
\v 7 I dwelt in the highest places, and my throne is in the pillar of a cloud.
\v 8 I alone have gone round about the compass of heaven, and have penetrated into the bottom of the depth, and have walked in the waves of the sea,
\v 9 and stood in all the earth: and in all people.
\v 10 and in every nation I have had the primacy:
\v 11 and I have by strength trodden down the hearts of all the excellent, and the base; and in all these things I sought rest, & I shall abide in the inheritance of our Lord. \f + \fr 24:11 \ft God offereth his grace, but forceth not any to accept it.\f*
\v 12 Then the creator of all commanded, and said to me: & he that created me, rested in my tabernacle, \f + \fr 24:12 \ft Creation is not here taken in the strict signification, but for divine production, in that God the Father by understanding begetteth God the Son. As likewise the Father and the Son by love produce the Holy Ghost.\f*
\v 13 and he said to me: Inhabit in Jacob, and inherit in Israel, and take root in mine elect. \f + \fr 24:13 \ft in the Church only is effectual grace.\f*
\v 14 From the beginning and before the worlds was I created, and unto the world to come I shall not cease, and in the holy habitation I have ministered before him.
\v 15 And so in Sion was I established, and in the sanctified city likewise I rested, and my power was in Jerusalem.
\v 16 And I took root in an honourable people, and in the portion of my God his inheritance, and my abiding is in the full assembly of saints.
\v 17 I am exalted as a cedar in Libanus, and as a cypress tree in mount Sion.
\v 18 As a palm tree in Cades am I exalted, and as a rose plant in Jericho:
\v 19 As a fair olive tree in the fields, and as a plane tree by the water in the streets am I exalted.
\v 20 I gave an odour as cinnamon, & aromatical balm: as chosen myrrh have I given the sweetness of odour:
\v 21 and as storax, and galbanum, and onyx, and aloes, and as Libanus not cut, have I perfumed mine habitation, and mine odour is as balm not mingled.
\v 22 I have spread out my boughs as the terebinth, and my boughs are of honour & grace.
\v 23 I as a vine have fructified sweetness of odour: and my flowers are fruit of honour and honesty.
\v 24 I am the mother of beautiful love, and of fear, and of knowledge, and of holy hope.
\v 25 In me is all grace of way and truth, in me all hope of life and virtue.
\v 26 Pass to me all ye that desire me, and be filled of my generations.
\v 27 For my spirit is sweet above honey, and mine inheritance above honey and the honey comb. \x + \xo 24:27 \xt Psa. 18.\x*
\v 28 My memory is unto generations of worlds.
\v 29 They that eat me, shall yet hunger: and they that drink me, shall yet thirst. \f + \fr 24:29 \ft The more grace any hath, the more he desireth and receiveth.\f*
\v 30 He that heareth me, shall not be confounded: and they that work in me, shall not sin.
\v 31 They that explicate me, shall have life everlasting.
\v 32 All these things are the book of life, and the testament of the Highest, & the knowledge of truth.
\v 33 Moyses commanded a law in the precepts of justices, and an inheritance to the house of Jacob, and the promises to Israel.
\v 34 He appointed to David his servant for to raise up a king of him most strong, and sitting in the throne of honour for ever. \f + \fr 24:34 \ft In David's progeny God preserved the kingly state till the captivity: and the estimation of the royal blood unto Christ. But in all this David was a figure of Christ, who sitteth in the Throne of honour absolutely for ever.\f*
\v 35 Who filleth wisdom as Phison, and as Tigris in the days of new fruits.
\v 36 Who replenisheth understanding as Euphrates, who multiplieth it as Jordan in the time of harvest. \x + \xo 24:36 \xt Iosu. 3.\x*
\v 37 Who sendeth discipline as the light, and assisting as Gehon in the day of vintage.
\v 38 Who first hath perfect knowledge of it, & a weaker shall not search it out.
\v 39 For her cogitation shall abound above the sea, and her counsels above the great depth.
\v 40 I wisdom have poured out rivers.
\v 41 I as a sluse of a mighty water out of the river, I as the river Dioryx, & as a water conduit I came out of paradise.
\v 42 Isaid: I will water my garden of plants, and will inebriate the fruit of my meadow.
\v 43 And behold my sluse was made aboundant, and my river came near to a sea.
\v 44 Because I illuminated doctrine to all as the morning light, & I will declare it far.
\v 45 I will penetrate all the inferior parts of the earth, and will behold all that sleep, and will illuminate all that hope in our Lord.
\v 46 I will yet pour out doctrine as prophecy, and will leave it to them that seek wisdom, and will not cease unto their progenies even to the holy age.
\v 47 See ye that I have not laboured for myself only, but for all that seek out the truth.
\c 25
\p
\v 1 In three things my spirit is pleased, which are approved before God, and men:
\v 2 The concord of brethren, and the love of neighbours, and man and wife well agreeing together. \f + \fr 25:2 \ft Three very commendable things.\f*
\v 3 Three sorts my soul hateth, and I am greatly grieved at their life:
\v 4 A poor man proud: & a rich man a liar: an old man a fool, and doting. \f + \fr 25:4 \ft Other three detestable.\f*
\v 5 The things that thou hast not gathered in thy youth, how shalt thou find them in thy old age?
\v 6 How beautiful is judgement for a gray head, and for ancients to know counsel!
\v 7 How beautiful is wisdom for the aged, & understanding glorious, and counsel!
\v 8 Much cunning is the crown of old men, and the fear of God is their glory.
\v 9 Nine things not to be imagined of the heart have I magnified, and the tenth I will tell unto men with my tongue: \f + \fr 25:9 \ft Nine happy things in this life.\f*
\v 10 Aman that hath joy in his children; living and seeing the subversion of his enemies.
\v 11 Blessed is he that dwelleth with a wise woman; & that hath not offended with his tongue; and that hath not served such as are unworthy of him. \x + \xo 25:11 \xt Iac. 3.\x*
\v 12 Blessed is he that findeth a true friend; and that declareth justice to an ear that heareth.
\v 13 How great is he, that findeth wisdom and knowledge; but he is not above him that feareth our Lord. \f + \fr 25:13 \ft All happiness in this life is grounded in the fear of God.\f*
\v 14 The fear of God hath set it-self above all things:
\v 15 blessed is the man, to whom is given to have the fear of God: he that holdeth it, to whom shall he be resembled?
\v 16 The fear of God is the beginning of his love: and the beginning of faith is to be fast joined unto it.
\v 17 The heaviness of the heart is all plague: & all malice, the wickedness of a woman. \f + \fr 25:17 \ft The description of heresy under the figure of a wicked woman: whose malice is secretly covered under pretence of truth and piety.\f*
\v 18 And he will see all plague, and not the plague of the heart:
\v 19 & all wickedness, & not the wickedness of a woman:
\v 20 and all obduction and not the obduction of them that hate him:
\v 21 and all revenge, and not the revenge of the enemies.
\v 22 There is no head worse than the head of a serpent:
\v 23 and there is no anger above the anger of a woman. It shall be more pleasant to abide with a lion and dragon, than to dwell with a wicked woman. \x + \xo 25:23 \xt Pro. 21.\x*
\v 24 The wickedness of a woman changeth her face: and darkeneth her countenance as a bear: and will shew it as a sack. In the midst of her neighbours,
\v 25 her husband groaned, and hearing he sighed a little.
\v 26 All malice is short to the malice of a woman, the lot of sinners fall upon her.
\v 27 As the going up a gravelly way in the feet of the aged, so a woman full of tongue to a quiet man.
\v 28 Look not upon a woman's beauty, and desire not a woman for beauty.
\v 29 Awoman's anger, and impudency, and confusion is great.
\v 30 Awoman if she have superiority, is contrary to her husband. \f + \fr 25:30 \ft Lay-head-ship in spiritual causes is so unreasonable and absurd, that few heretics will endure it.\f*
\v 31 An humbled heart, and heavy countenance, and plague of heart, is a wicked woman.
\v 32 Feeble hands, and disjointed knees, a woman that doth not make her husband happy.
\v 33 From woman came the beginning of sin, and by her we do all die.
\v 34 Give not issue to thy water, no not a little: nor to a wicked woman leave to go forth.
\v 35 If she walk not at thine hand, she will confound thee in the sight of thine enemies.
\v 36 Cut her off from thy flesh, lest she always abuse thee.
\c 26
\p
\v 1 The husband of a good wife is happy: for the number of his years is double. \f + \fr 26:1 \ft An unquiet life depriveth a man of much comfort: and therefore continual peace is as double life.\f*
\v 2 Astrong woman delighteth her husband, and shall accomplish the years of his life in peace.
\v 3 Agood woman is a good portion, in the good portion of them that fear God shall she be given to a man for good deeds:
\v 4 And the heart of rich and poor is good, at all time their countenance is merry.
\v 5 Of three things my heart hath been afraid, and at the fourth my face hath trembled:
\v 6 The betraying of a city, and a gathering together of the people:
\v 7 false calumny, all more grievous than death.
\v 8 Ajealous woman is the sorrow and mourning of the heart.
\v 9 In a jealous woman is a scourge of the tongue, communicating with all.
\v 10 As a yoke of oxen that is moved, so also a wicked woman: he that holdeth her, is as he that taketh hold of a scorpion. \f + \fr 26:10 \ft As when oxen move, the yoke on their necks doth move withal: so a wicked woman (to wit heresy) cannot rest, nor let others rest quiet.\f*
\v 11 Awoman given to drunkenness is great anger: & her contumely and turpitude shall not be hid.
\v 12 The fornication of a woman shall be known in the lifting up of her eyes, and in her eye-lids.
\v 13 On thy daughter that turneth not away herself, set sure watch: lest occasion found she abuse herself.
\v 14 Take heed of the impudency of her eyes, and marvel not if she contemn thee.
\v 15 As a wayfaring man that thirsteth, will she open her mouth to the fountain, and will drink of every water that is next, & will sit against every hedge, and open her quiver against every arrow, until she fail.
\v 16 The grace of a diligent woman shall delight her husband, and shall fat his bones. \f + \fr 26:16 \ft The Catholic faith is the ground of all virtues.\f*
\v 17 Her discipline is the gift of God.
\v 18 Awise and still woman, there is no exchange for a soul instructed.
\v 19 Aholy, and shamefast woman, is grace upon grace.
\v 20 And all weight is not worthy a continent soul.
\v 21 As the sun rising to the world in the highest places of God, so is the beauty of a good woman for an ornament of her house.
\v 22 Alamp shining upon the holy candlestick, & the beauty of the face upon stayed age.
\v 23 Pillars of gold upon feet of silver, and stable feet upon the soles of a stayed woman.
\v 24 Eternal foundations upon a sound rock, and the commandments of God in the heart of a holy woman.
\v 25 At two things my heart is grieved, and at the third anger is come upon me:
\v 26 Aman of war decaying by poverty: and a wise man contemned:
\v 27 and he that transgresseth from justice to sin, God hath prepared him to the sword.
\v 28 Two sorts have appeared unto me hard and dangerous, a merchant is hardly rid of negligence: and a viteler shall not be justified from the sins of the lips. \f + \fr 26:28 \ft Those that keep inns or ale-houses are always talking, as willing to please all, but in much talk wanteth not sin. Pro. 10. v. 19.\f*
\c 27
\p
\v 1 Through poverty many have offended: and he that seeketh to be made rich, turneth away his eye. \x + \xo 27:1 \xt 1. Tim. 6.\x*
\v 2 As a stake is fastened in the midst of stones compact together, so also in the midst of selling and buying, sin shall be straitened.
\v 3 Sin shall be destroyed with the sinner.
\v 4 If thou hold not thyself instantly in the fear of our Lord, thy house shall quickly be subverted. \f + \fr 27:4 \ft The soul is kept in good state by fearing God.\f*
\v 5 As in the shaking of a sieve the dust will remain: so the perplexity of a man in his cogitation. \f + \fr 27:5 \ft After that sin is purged there remain relics in the soul, as dust in a sieve when the chaff is cast out, till it be more purged or washed. Psal. 50. v. 4.\f*
\v 6 The furnace trieth the potter's vessels, and the tentation of tribulation just men. \x + \xo 27:6 \xt Prov. 27.\x*
\v 7 As the husbandry about a tree sheweth the fruit thereof, so a word out of the thought of the heart of man.
\v 8 Praise not a man before full discourse, for this is the trial of men.
\v 9 If thou follow justice, thou shalt apprehend it: and shalt put it on as a long robe of honour, and thou shalt dwell with it: and it shall protect thee for ever, and in the day of acknowledging thou shalt find steadfastness.
\v 10 The fowls flock together to their like: and truth shall return to them that work it.
\v 11 The lion always lieth in wait for a prey: so sins for them that work iniquities.
\v 12 Aholy man continueth in wisdom as the sun: for a fool is changed as the moon. \f + \fr 27:12 \ft Whether the sun shineth forth or not, it is always light: so is a wise man always virtuous, whether it appear outwardly or no.\f* \f + \fr 27:12 \ft Afool, or wicked man, hath no light of virtue in himself (like the moon) but sometimes seemeth to have more light, sometimes less, sometimes none at all. S. Bernard.\f*
\v 13 In the midst of the unwise keep the word till his time: but in the midst of deep considerers be continually.
\v 14 The narration of sinners is odious, & their laughter is in the delights of sin.
\v 15 Speech that sweareth much shall make the hair of the head to stand upright: and his lack of reverence is the stopping of the ears.
\v 16 Shedding of blood is in the brawling of the proud: and their cursing is a grievous hearing.
\v 17 He that discloseth the secret of a friend loseth credit, and he shall not find a friend to his mind.
\v 18 Love thy neighbour, and be joined with him in fidelity.
\v 19 But if thou discover his secrets, thou shalt not pursue after him.
\v 20 For as a man that loseth his friend, so also he that loseth the friendship of his neighbour.
\v 21 And as he that letteth a bird go out of his hand, so hast thou left thy neighbour, & shalt not take him.
\v 22 Follow him not, because he is far absent, for he is fled, as a doe out of the snare: because his soul is wounded.
\v 23 Thou canst no more bind him, and of a curse there is reconciliation:
\v 24 but to disclose the secrets of a friend, is the desperation of an unhappy soul.
\v 25 He that winketh with the eye, forgeth wicked things, and no man will cast him off: \x + \xo 27:25 \xt Pro. 10.\x*
\v 26 in the sight of thine eyes he will sweeten his mouth, and will be in admiration upon thy words: but at the last he will pervert his mouth, and in thy words he will lay a scandal.
\v 27 I have heard many things, & have not esteemed them equal to him, and our Lord will hate him.
\v 28 He that casteth a stone on high, it will fall upon his head: & the deceitful stroke will divide the wounds of the deceitful. \f + \fr 27:28 \ft He that expressly doth injury to another is justly punished also in this world.\f* \f + \fr 27:28 \ft How secretly so ever any hurteth another, he woundeth his own conscience, and cannot escape God's judgement.\f*
\v 29 He that diggeth a pit, shall fall into it: and he that setteth a stone for his neighbour, shall stumble on it: & he that layeth a snare for another, shall perish in it. \x + \xo 27:29 \xt Pro. 26. Eccl. 10.\x*
\v 30 To a man that doth most wicked counsel, it shall be turned upon himself, and he shall not know from whence it cometh to him.
\v 31 Derision & reproach of the proud, and vengeance as a lion shall lie in wait for him.
\v 32 They shall perish in a snare that are delighted with the fall of the just: and sorrow shall consume them before they die.
\v 33 Anger and fury, both are execrable, and the sinful man shall be subject to them.
\c 28
\p
\v 1 He that will be revenged, shall find revenge of our Lord, and keeping he will keep his sin. \f + \fr 28:1 \ft He that seeketh revenge contrary to the course of justice, or of evil intention or of rancor of mind, sinneth grievously.\f*
\v 2 Forgive thy neighbour hurting thee: & then shall thy sins be loosed to thee when thou prayest.
\v 3 Man to man reserveth anger, and doth he seek remedy of God?
\v 4 He hath not mercy on a man like unto himself, and doth he entreat for his own sins?
\v 5 Himself whereas he is flesh, reserveth anger, and doth he ask propitiation of God? Who by prayer shall obtain for his sin?
\v 6 Remember the last things, & cease to be at enmity:
\v 7 for consumption and death are imminent in his commandments.
\v 8 Remember the fear of God, and be not angry with thy neighbour.
\v 9 Remember the testament of the High, & contemn the ignorance of thy neighbour.
\v 10 Refrain thyself from strife, and thou shalt diminish thy sins:
\v 11 for an angry man kindleth strife, and a sinful man will trouble his friends, and in the midst of them that are at peace he will cast in enmity.
\v 12 For according to the wood of the forest, so the fire burneth: and according to the power of a man, so shall his anger be, and according to his substance he will increase his anger. \x + \xo 28:12 \xt Prov. 26.\x*
\v 13 Hasty contention kindleth a fire: & hasty strife sheddeth blood: and an ill testifying tongue bringeth death.
\v 14 If thou blow upon a spark, it will burn as a fire: and if thou spit thereon, it shall be quenched: both proceed out of the mouth.
\v 15 The whisperer & double tongued is accurst: for he hath troubled many that were at peace.
\v 16 A third tongue hath moved many, and dispersed them from nation into nation. \f + \fr 28:16 \ft Undiscreet report to one what another hath said, is often cause of much discontentment and of dissension.\f*
\v 17 It hath destroyed the walled cities of the rich, and hath digged down the houses of great men.
\v 18 It hath cut the forces of peoples, and undone strong nations.
\v 19 Athird tongue hath cast out many women, and deprived them of their labours.
\v 20 He that regardeth it, shall not have rest, neither shall he have a friend in whom he may repose.
\v 21 The stroke of a whip maketh a blue mark: but the stroke of the tongue will break the bones.
\v 22 Many have fallen by the edge of the sword, but not so as they that have perished by their tongue.
\v 23 Blessed is he that is covered from a wicked tongue, that hath not passed into the anger thereof, and that hath not drawn the yoke thereof, and hath not been tied in the bands thereof:
\v 24 for the yoke of it is a yoke of iron: and the band of it is a band of brass.
\v 25 The death of it, is a most wicked death: and hell is more profitable than it.
\v 26 The continuance of it shall not be permanent, but it shall obtain the ways of the unjust: and it shall not burn the just in the flame thereof.
\v 27 They that forsake God, shall fall into it, and it shall burn in them, and shall not be quenched, and it shall be sent in upon them as a lion, and as a leopard it shall hurt them.
\v 28 Hedge thine ears with thorns, and hear not a wicked tongue, and make doors to thy mouth, and locks. \f + \fr 28:28 \ft To hear detraction is as bad as to speak it.\f*
\v 29 Lay together thy silver, and make balance to thy words, and right bridles to thy mouth:
\v 30 and take heed lest perhaps thou slip in thy tongue, & fall in the sight of the enemies, that lie in wait for thee, and thy fall be uncurable unto death.
\c 29
\p
\v 1 He that lendeth to his neighbour, doth mercy: and he that prevaileth with hand, keepeth the commandments. \f + \fr 29:1 \ft Lending is a work of mercy, & a kind of alms. To repay that is borrowed is a work of justice, wittingly not to restore is as bad as theft.\f*
\v 2 Lend to thy neighbour in the time of his necessity, and again repay thy neighbour in his time. \f + \fr 29:2 \ft See previous note\f*
\v 3 Confirm thy word, and do faithfully with him: & thou shalt find at all time, that which is necessary for thee.
\v 4 Many have esteemed a thing lent as a thing found, and have given molestation to them that did help them.
\v 5 Till they receive, they kiss the hands of the lender, and in promises they humble their voice:
\v 6 and in the time of repaying they will ask a time, and will speak words of tediousness and murmurings, and will make the time an excuse:
\v 7 and if he be able to pay, he will resist, he will pay scarce half of the whole, and will account it as a thing found:
\v 8 but if not, he will defraud him of his money, and possess him an enemy without cause:
\v 9 and will repay him reproaches and curses, and for honour and benefit will repay him contumely.
\v 10 Many have not lent, not because of wickedness, but they were afraid to be defrauded without cause.
\v 11 But yet upon the humble be stronger of mind, & for alms defer him not.
\v 12 Because of the commandment receive the poor: and because of his poverty, send him not away empty.
\v 13 Lose money for thy brother and thy friend: and hide it not under a stone unto perdition. \x + \xo 29:13 \xt Exo. 22. Deu. 14.\x*
\v 14 Put thy treasure in the precepts of the Highest, & it shall profit thee more than gold. \f + \fr 29:14 \ft Great fruit of works of mercy.\f*
\v 15 Shut up alms in the heart of the poor, and the same shall obtain for thee against all evil.
\v 16 The alms a man giveth is as a purse with him: it will conserve his grace as the ball of the eye. \x + \xo 29:16 \xt Tob. 4.\x*
\v 17 And furthermore will raise up and render reward to every one upon their heads.
\v 18 Above the shield of the mighty, & above the spear, it shall fight against thine enemy.
\v 19 Agood man becometh surety for his neighbour: and he that hath lost shame, will leave him to himself.
\v 20 Forget not the kindness of a surety: for he hath given his life for thee.
\v 21 The sinner and unclean person flyeth from his surety.
\v 22 Asinner counteth the goods of his surety to himself: and unthankful in mind, will forsake him that delivered him.
\v 23 Aman is surety for his neighbour: and when he hath lost shame, he shall be forsaken of him.
\v 24 Naughty suretyship hath undone many that were in good case, and hath tossed them as a wave of the sea.
\v 25 Whurling round about, it hath made mighty men to remove, and they have wandered in strange nations.
\v 26 Asinner that transgresseth the commandment of our Lord, shall fall into naughty suretyship: and he that endeavoureth to do many things, shall fall into judgement.
\v 27 Recover thy neighbour according to thy power, and take heed to thyself that thou fall not. \f + \fr 29:27 \ft Prudence requireth that by helping another, thou doest not overthrow thyself.\f*
\v 28 The beginning of man's life water & bread, and garment, and house covering his turpitude.
\v 29 Better is the poor man's fare under a roof of boards, than sumptuous cheer in a strange place without a house.
\v 30 Let the least thing please thee in stead of a great, and thou shalt not hear the reproach of peregrination.
\v 31 It is a naughty life to change lodging from house to house: and where he shall lodge, he shall not deal boldly, nor open his mouth.
\v 32 He shall lodge, and feed, and make the unthankful drink, and beside these things he shall hear bitter words.
\v 33 Pass thou stranger & furnish the table, & with the things thou hast in thy hand, feed the rest.
\v 34 Depart from the presence of the honour of my friends: for the necessity of my house my brother is to be lodged with me.
\v 35 These things be grievous to a man that hath understanding: rebuke for the house, and the reproach of the lender.
\c 30
\p
\v 1 He that loveth his son, doth accustom him to stripes, that he may rejoice in his later end, and not grope after the doors of his neighbours. \x + \xo 30:1 \xt Pro. 13. & 23.\x*
\v 2 He that teacheth his son, shall be praised in him, & in the midst of them of his household he shall glory in him.
\v 3 He that teacheth his son, doth cast the enemy into emulation, and in the midst of his friends he shall glory in him.
\v 4 His father is dead, & he is as it were not dead: for he hath left behind him the like to himself. \x + \xo 30:4 \xt Deut. 6.\x*
\v 5 In his life he saw and rejoiced in him: in his death he was not made sorry, neither was he confounded before the enemies.
\v 6 For he left a defender of his house against the enemies, & one that should render thank to his friends.
\v 7 For the souls of his sons he will bind up his wounds, & at every voice his bowels shall be troubled. \f + \fr 30:7 \ft The eldest son being heir to his father, is to have special care of the other children, even to the adventuring of his own hurt for their lives.\f*
\v 8 An untamed horse becometh stubborn, and a dissolute child will become heady.
\v 9 Pamper thy son, and he will make thee afraid: play with him, and he will make thee sorrowful.
\v 10 Laugh not with him, lest thou be sorry, and at the last thy teeth shall be on edge. \f + \fr 30:10 \ft Teeth on edge or gnashing of teeth, is a part of hell pains. Mat 8. & 13. & sometimes beginneth in this life.\f*
\v 11 Give him not power in his youth, and contemn not his cogitations.
\v 12 Curb his neck in youth, and knock his sides whilst he is a child, lest perhaps he be hardened, and believe thee not, and he shall be sorrow of mind to thee.
\v 13 Teach thy son, and work in him, that thou offend not in his dishonesty.
\v 14 Better is a poor man whole and strong of force, than a rich man weak and scourged with misery.
\v 15 The health of the soul in holiness of justice, is better than all gold and silver: and a sound body, than infinite revenues. \f + \fr 30:15 \ft Piety is above riches and honour.\f*
\v 16 There is no riches above the riches of the health of the body: and there is no delight above the joy of the heart.
\v 17 Better is death than a bitter life: and everlasting rest, than continual sickness.
\v 18 Good things hid in a mouth that is shut, are as messes of meats set about a grave.
\v 19 What shall sacrifice profit an idol? For neither shall he eat, nor smell: \x + \xo 30:19 \xt Deu. 14.\x*
\v 20 so he that is chased away of our Lord, beareth the rewards of iniquity:
\v 21 seeing with his eyes, & groaning, as an eunuch embracing a virgin and sighing.
\v 22 Give not heaviness to thy soul, & afflict not thyself in thy counsel. \f + \fr 30:22 \ft Suffer not unnecessary pensiveness to afflict thy mind, through pusillanimity.\f* \x + \xo 30:22 \xt Pro. 12. 15. & 17.\x*
\v 23 Joyfulness of the heart, this is the life of a man, and a treasure without defect of holiness: and the joy of a man is long life.
\v 24 Have mercy on thine own soul, pleasing God, and refrain: and comfort thy heart in his holiness: and expel sorrow far from thee. \f + \fr 30:24 \ft But rely wholly upon God's will and providence, resigning thy will unto his.\f*
\v 25 For sorrow hath killed many, and there is no profit in it.
\v 26 Envy and anger diminish the days, and thought will bring old age before the time.
\v 27 Amagnifical heart is good in banquets: for his banquets are made diligently.
\c 31
\p
\v 1 Watching after honesty shall pine the flesh, & the thought thereof taketh away sleep. \f + \fr 31:1 \ft They that employ all their study to get virtues, shall be more free from tentations of the flesh.\f* \f + \fr 31:1 \ft And from drowsiness of mind: whereupon S. Ierom admonisheth: Love the studies of holy Scriptures, and thou wilt not love the vices of the flesh. Epist. ad Rusticum Monach.\f*
\v 2 The thought of foreknowledge turneth away the understanding, & grievous infirmity maketh a sober soul.
\v 3 The rich man hath laboured in gathering of substance together, & in his rest he shall be replenished with his goods.
\v 4 The poor man hath laboured in the diminishing of his living, and in the end he is made poor.
\v 5 He that loveth gold shall not be justified: & he that followeth after corruption, shall be replenished of it.
\v 6 Many have been given into falls for gold, and their perdition hath come by the beauty thereof.
\v 7 The gold of them that sacrifice is a wood of offence: woe to them, that follow after it, and every unwise man shall perish in it.
\v 8 Blessed is the rich man that is found without spot: and that hath not gone after gold, nor hoped in money and treasures.
\v 9 Who is this? & we will praise him, for he hath done marvelous things in his life.
\v 10 Who is proved therein, & perfect, shall have eternal glory. He that could transgress, & hath not transgressed: and do evils, and hath not done: \f + \fr 31:10 \ft It is in man's freewill to transgress, & therefore they are happy, that through God's grace do not break his commandments.\f*
\v 11 therefore are his good things established in our Lord, & all the church of saints shall declare his alms.
\v 12 Art thou set at a great table? Open not thy jaw thereupon first.
\v 13 Say not this: There be many things which are upon it.
\v 14 Remember that a naughty eye is evil.
\v 15 What is created worse than the eye? Therefore shall it weep at every face. When it shall see,
\v 16 stretch not out thy hand first, & so contaminated with envy thou be ashamed.
\v 17 Be not oppressed in a feast.
\v 18 Understand by thyself what thy neighbour's things are.
\v 19 Use as a frugal man those things, that are set before thee: lest thou be hated when thou eatest much. \x + \xo 31:19 \xt Pro. 23.\x*
\v 20 Leave off first for manner's sake, and exceed not, lest thou perhaps offend.
\v 21 And if thou be set in the midst of many, stretch not forth thy hand before them: neither do thou first ask to drink.
\v 22 How sufficient is a little wine for a man well taught, and in sleeping thou shalt not be pained with it, and thou shalt feel no grief.
\v 23 Watching, & choler, & torment to an unsatiable man:
\v 24 sleep of health is in a man of spare diet: he shall sleep until morning, and his soul with him shall be delighted.
\v 25 And if thou hast been forced with eating much, rise from the midst, and vomit, and it shall refresh thee, and thou shalt not bring infirmity to thy body.
\v 26 Hear me my son, and despise me not: and in the end thou shalt find my words.
\v 27 In all thy works be quick, and all infirmity shall not chance unto thee.
\v 28 The lips of many shall bless him that is magnifical in breads, and the testimony of his truth is faithful. \x + \xo 31:28 \xt Pro. 22.\x*
\v 29 In naughty bread the city will murmur, and the testimony of the naughtiness thereof is true. \f + \fr 31:29 \ft As bread is the chief sustenance of the body, so doctrine is of the mind, which being good nourisheth, & if it be bad corrupteth them that receive it.\f*
\v 30 Provoke not them that love wine: for wine hath destroyed very many.
\v 31 Fire trieth hard iron: so wine drunken in drunkenness shall rebuke the hearts of the proud.
\v 32 Equal life to all men, wine in sobriety: if thou drink it moderately, thou shalt be sober.
\v 33 What is his life that is diminished with wine?
\v 34 What defraudeth life? Death.
\v 35 Wine was created for joyfulness, and not for drunkenness from the beginning. \x + \xo 31:35 \xt Prov. 31. Psa. 103.\x*
\v 36 Wine drunken moderately is the joy of the soul and the heart.
\v 37 Sober drinking is health to soul and body.
\v 38 Much wine drunken maketh provocation, & wrath, & many ruins.
\v 39 Much wine drunken is bitterness of the soul.
\v 40 The courageousness of drunkenness is offence of the unwise, lessening the strength, and making wounds.
\v 41 In a banquet of wine rebuke not thy neighbour: and despise him not in his mirth.
\v 42 Speak not to him words of reproach: and press him not in demanding again.
\c 32
\p
\v 1 Have they made thee Ruler? Be not extolled: be among them as one of them. \f + \fr 32:1 \ft Humility is necessary in all, but most especially in men of authority. The greatest art in this life is to contemn vain glory in height of authority. S. Greg. de cura pastorali.\f*
\v 2 Have care of them, and so sit thou still, and all thy care being dispatched, repose.
\v 3 That thou mayst rejoice for their sakes, & receive a crown as an ornament of grace, and obtain the dignity of the contribution.
\v 4 Speak thou that art elder: for it becometh thee,
\v 5 the first word to him that loveth with knowledge, & hinder not music.
\v 6 Where there is no hearing, pour not out speech, and extol not thyself out of time in thy wisdom.
\v 7 Alittle pearl of the carbuncle in an ornament of gold, and the comparison of musicians in a banquet of wine.
\v 8 As a signet of the emerald is in the working of gold: so the melody of music is joyful and moderate wine.
\v 9 Hear holding thy peace, & for thy reverence good grace shall come to thee.
\v 10 Young man speak in thine own cause scarcely.
\v 11 If thou be asked twice, let thine answer have an head.
\v 12 In many things be as it were ignorant, and hear holding thy peace and withal asking.
\v 13 In the midst of great men presume not: & where ancients are, speak not much.
\v 14 before hail there shall go lightning: & grace shall go before shamefastness, & for thy reverence good grace shall come to thee.
\v 15 And at the hour of rising slack not thyself: but run before first into thy house, and there withdraw thyself, and there play,
\v 16 and do thy conceits, and not in sins and proud word.
\v 17 And above all these things bless our Lord that made thee, & that doth replenish thee with all his goods.
\v 18 He that feareth our Lord, shall receive his doctrine: and they that will watch after him, shall find blessing.
\v 19 He that seeketh the law shall be replenished with it: and he that doth deceitfully, shall be scandalized by it.
\v 20 They that fear our Lord, shall find just judgement, and shall kindle justices as light.
\v 21 Asinful man will fly reprehension, and according to his will, will find excuse.
\v 22 Aman of counsel will not destroy understanding, an alien and proud man will not dread fear:
\v 23 Yea after he hath done with fear without counsel, he shall be controlled even by his own pursuits.
\v 24 Son do nothing without counsel, and after the fact thou shalt not repent. \f + \fr 32:24 \ft God directeth men's resolutions, and actions, when they use the means of consultation, as he hath appointed: for when two or three are gathered in his name, he is in midst of them. Mat. 18.\f*
\v 25 Go not in the way of ruin, and thou shalt not stumble at stones: commit not thyself to a laborious way, lest thou set a scandal to thy soul.
\v 26 And beware of thy children, and take heed of them of thy household.
\v 27 In all thy work believe thy soul by faith: for this is the keeping of the commandments. \f + \fr 32:27 \ft Do not against thy conscience.\f*
\v 28 He that believeth God attendeth to the commandments: and he that trusteth in him, shall not be lessened.
\c 33
\p
\v 1 To him that feareth our Lord evils shall not happen, but in tentation God will keep him, and deliver him from evils.
\v 2 Awise man hateth not the commandments and justices, and he shall not be shaken as a ship in a storm.
\v 3 Aman of understanding believeth the law of God, and the law is sure to him.
\v 4 He that repeateth an interrogation, shall better prepare his answer, and so shall be heard, and shall keep discipline.
\v 5 The heart of a fool is as a wheel of a cart: & his cogitation as a turning axletree. \f + \fr 33:5 \ft Men led with passions run from one vice into another without ceasing. Especially heretics run into many errors. Against which S. Paul prescribeth this rule: It is best that the heart be established with grace. Heb. 13. v. 9.\f*
\v 6 Astallion horse neigheth under every one that sitteth upon him, so a friend that is a scorner.
\v 7 Why doth one day excel another, and one light another, and one year another year of the sun?
\v 8 By the knowledge of our Lord they were separated, the sun being made, and keeping the precept.
\v 9 And he changed times, and the festival days thereof, and in the same they celebrated the festival days at an hour.
\v 10 Of them God exalted and magnified, and of them he put into the number of days. And all men are of the ground, and of the earth, from whence Adam was created.
\v 11 In the multitude of the discipline of our Lord he separated them, and changed their ways.
\v 12 Of them he blessed, and exalted: and of them he sanctified, and applied to himself: and of them he cursed and humbled, and converted them from their separation.
\v 13 As potter's clay is in his hand, to fashion and dispose it. \x + \xo 33:13 \xt Rom. 9.\x*
\v 14 All his ways according to his disposition: so man in the hand of him, and he will render to him according to his judgement.
\v 15 Against evil is good, and against death life: so also against a just man a sinner. And so look upon all the works of the Highest. Two against two, and one against one.
\v 16 And I awaked last, and as he that gathereth berries after the grape gatherers.
\v 17 In the blessing of God I also have hoped: and as he that gathereth grapes, have I filled the wine press.
\v 18 See that I have not laboured for myself only, but for all that seek out discipline.
\v 19 Hear me ye great men, and all peoples, and ye rulers of the Church harken with your ears.
\v 20 To son and wife, brother and friend, give not power over thee in thy life: and give not thy possession to another: lest perhaps thou repent thee, and thou entreat for them.
\v 21 Whilst thou art yet alive and takest breath, all flesh shall not change thee.
\v 22 For it is better that thy children ask of thee, than that thou look toward the hands of thy children.
\v 23 In all thy works be exquisite.
\v 24 Give no stain to thy glory. In the day of the consummation of the days of thy life, and in the time of thy decease distribute thine inheritance.
\v 25 Fodder, and wand, and burden for an ass: bread, and discipline, and work for a servant.
\v 26 He worketh in discipline, and seeketh to rest: release him his hands, and he seeketh liberty.
\v 27 The yoke and the rein bend a stiff neck, and continual works do bow a servant.
\v 28 For a malicious servant torment & fetters, send him into work, that he be not idle.
\v 29 For idleness hath taught much naughtiness.
\v 30 Set him to work: for so it becometh him. And if he be not obedient, bow him with fetters, and exceed not over all flesh: but without judgement do no grievous thing.
\v 31 If thou have a faithful servant, let him be unto thee as thy soul: as a brother so entreat him: because in the blood of thy soul thou hast gotten him.
\v 32 If thou hurt him unjustly, he will run away:
\v 33 if rising up he depart, thou knowest not whom to ask, and what way to seek him.
\c 34
\p
\v 1 Vain hope & lying is to a foolish man: & dreams extol the unwise. \f + \fr 34:1 \ft Vain dreams are not to be regarded: but some are good, & from God. Gen. 37. 40. 41. Dan. 2. 4. Mat. 1.\f*
\v 2 As he that apprehendeth a shadow, and pursueth the wind: so is he also that attendeth to lying visions.
\v 3 According to this is the vision of dreams: as a man's similitude before the face of a man.
\v 4 Of the unclean what shall be made clean? And of a liar what truth shall be said?
\v 5 Divination of error, and lying soothsayings, and the dreams of them that do evil, are vanity.
\v 6 And as a woman that travaileth, thy heart suffereth phantasies: unless it be a vision sent forth from the Highest, set not thy heart upon them.
\v 7 For dreams have made many to err, and they that hoped in them have failed.
\v 8 The word of the law shall be fulfilled without lying, and wisdom in the mouth of the faithful shall be made plain. \f + \fr 34:8 \ft Whatsoever is written in holy Scripture is undoubtedly true: and no jot of the law shall perish.\f* \f + \fr 34:8 \ft God also provideth that always there be some which truly explicate his law.\f*
\v 9 He that hath not been proved, what knoweth he? A man expert in many things, shall think many things: and he that hath learned many things, shall declare understanding.
\v 10 He that is not tried, knoweth few things: and he that hath been in many things, multiplieth wickedness.
\v 11 He that hath not been proved, what manner of things knoweth he? He that is deceived, shall abound with wickedness.
\v 12 I have seen many things in wandering to and fro, and very many fashions of words.
\v 13 Sometimes I have been in danger unto death for these things, and I was delivered by the grace of God.
\v 14 The spirit of them that fear God is sought, & at his sight shall be blessed.
\v 15 For their hope is on him that saveth them, and the eyes of God upon them that love him.
\v 16 He that feareth our Lord shall tremble at nothing, and shall not dread: because he is his hope.
\v 17 His soul is blessed that feareth our Lord.
\v 18 To whom doth he look, and who is his strength?
\v 19 The eyes of our Lord are upon them that fear him, a protector of might, a stay of strength, a cover from the heat, and shadow for the noon time, \x + \xo 34:19 \xt Psal. 32.\x*
\v 20 a saving from offence, and help from falling, exalting the soul, and illuminating the eyes, giving health, and life, and blessing.
\v 21 The oblation of him that immolateth of an unjust thing is spotted, and the scornings of the unjust are not acceptable. \x + \xo 34:21 \xt Pro. 21. v. 27.\x*
\v 22 Our Lord is only theirs that expect him in the way of truth and justice. \x + \xo 34:22 \xt Prov. 15. v. 8.\x*
\v 23 The Highest alloweth not the gifts of the wicked: neither hath he regard to the oblations of the unjust, neither will he be made propitious for sins by the multitude of their sacrifices.
\v 24 He that offereth sacrifice of poor men's substance, is as he that sacrificeth the son in the presence of his father.
\v 25 The bread of the needy, is the life of the poor: he that defraudeth it, is a man of blood.
\v 26 He that taketh away bread in sweat, is as he that killeth his neighbour. \x + \xo 34:26 \xt Levi. 19.\x*
\v 27 He that sheddeth blood, and that defraudeth the hired man, are brethren.
\v 28 One building, and another destroying: what profit have they but the labour? \f + \fr 34:28 \ft He that destroyeth that another buildeth, bringeth two men's labours to nothing.\f*
\v 29 One praying, and another cursing: whether's voice will God hear?
\v 30 He that is washed from the dead, and toucheth him again, what doth his washing profit? \f + \fr 34:30 \ft Recidivation into sin maketh the former repentance frustrate. Mat. 18. v. 33.\f*
\v 31 so a man that fasteth in his sins: and doing the same again, what doth he profit in humbling himself? Who will hear his prayer?
\c 35
\p
\v 1 He that keepeth the law, multiplieth oblation.
\v 2 It is an wholesome sacrifice to attend to the commandments, and to depart from all iniquity.
\v 3 And to offer propitiation by sacrifice for injustices, and to retire from injustice is prayer for sins.
\v 4 He who offereth the flour of wheat, shall give thanks: and he that is merciful offereth sacrifice.
\v 5 To depart from iniquity is a thing that pleaseth our Lord well, and to depart from injustice is an entreating for sins.
\v 6 Thou shalt not appear before the sight of our Lord empty.
\v 7 For all these things are done because of the commandment of God.
\v 8 The oblation of the just maketh a fat altar, and is an odour of sweetness in the sight of the Highest.
\v 9 The sacrifice of the just is acceptable, and our Lord will not forget the memory thereof.
\v 10 Render glory to God with a good mind: and diminish not the first fruits of thine hands.
\v 11 In every gift make thy countenance cheerful, and in joyfulness sanctify thy tithes. \x + \xo 35:11 \xt 2. Cor. 9. Tob. 4.\x*
\v 12 Give to the Highest according to his gift, and with a good eye do according to the ability of thine hands:
\v 13 because our Lord is a rewarder, and will repay thee seven times so much. \f + \fr 35:13 \ft Oftentimes so much. As Prov. 24. Seven times shall the just fall, & shall rise again.\f*
\v 14 Offer not wicked gifts, for he will not receive them. \x + \xo 35:14 \xt Levit. 22. Deu. 15.\x*
\v 15 And look not upon an unjust sacrifice, because our Lord is judge, and there is not with him the glory of person.
\v 16 Our Lord will not accept person against the poor, and he will hear the prayer of him that is hurt. \x + \xo 35:16 \xt 2. Paral. 19. Rom. 2. Act. 10.\x*
\v 17 He will not despise the prayers of the pupil: nor the widow, if she pour out speech of mourning.
\v 18 Do not the widow's tears run down the cheek, & her exclamation upon him that causeth them to run?
\v 19 For from the cheek they go up even to heaven, and our Lord the hearer will not be delighted in them.
\v 20 He that adoreth God in delectation, shall be received, & his petition shall approach even to the clouds.
\v 21 The prayer of him that humbleth himself, shall penetrate the clouds: and till it approach he will not be comforted: and he will not depart till the Highest behold.
\v 22 And our Lord will not be long, but will judge the just, and will do judgement: and the strongest will not have patience in them, that he may crush their back:
\v 23 and he will repay vengeance to the Gentiles, till he take away the multitude of the proud: & break the sceptres of the unjust,
\v 24 till he reward men according to their doings: and according to the works of Adam, and according to his presumption.
\v 25 till he judge the judgement of his people, and shall delight the just with his mercy:
\v 26 The mercy of God is beautiful in the time of tribulation, as a cloud of rain in the time of drought.
\c 36
\p
\v 1 Have mercy upon us o God of all, and respect us, and shew us the light of thy mercies:
\v 2 and send in thy fear upon the nations, that have not sought after thee, that they may know that there is no God but thou, and that they may shew forth thy glorious things. \f + \fr 36:2 \ft This prayer implieth also a prophecy of the conversion of the Gentiles, as the like very often in the Psalms. 58. 64. 65. &c.\f*
\v 3 Lift up thy hand over the strange Nations, that they may see thy might.
\v 4 For as in their sight thou art sanctified in us, so in our sight thou shalt be magnified in them,
\v 5 that they may know thee, as we also have known, that there is no God beside thee o Lord.
\v 6 Renew signs, and change marvels.
\v 7 Glorify thy hand, and thy right arm.
\v 8 Raise up fury, and pour out wrath.
\v 9 Take away the adversary, and afflict the enemy.
\v 10 Hasten the time, and remember the end, that they may declare thy marvels.
\v 11 Let him that is saved be devoured in the wrath of flame: and let them that evil entreat thy people, find perdition.
\v 12 Break the head of Princes of the enemies, that say: There is none other beside us.
\v 13 Gather together all the tribes of Jacob: and let them know that there is no God but thou, that they may declare thy great works: & thou shalt inherit them as from the beginning.
\v 14 Have mercy on thy people, upon which thy name is invocated: and upon Israel, whom thou hast made equal to thy first begotten. \x + \xo 36:14 \xt Exo. 4.\x*
\v 15 Have mercy on the city of thy sanctification Jerusalem, the city of thy rest.
\v 16 Replenish Sion with thy words that cannot be uttered, & thy people with thy glory.
\v 17 Give the testimony to them that are thy creatures from the beginning, and raise up the prophecies, which the former prophets spake in thy name.
\v 18 Give reward to them that patiently expect thee, that thy prophets may be found faithful: and hear the prayers of thy servants,
\v 19 according to Aaron's benediction of thy people, and direct us into the way of justice, and let all know that inhabit the earth, that thou art God the beholder of the worlds. \x + \xo 36:19 \xt Num. 6.\x*
\v 20 The belly will eat all meat, and one meat is better than another meat. \f + \fr 36:20 \ft As there is difference of meats:\f*
\v 21 The jaws taste venison, & the wise heart lying words, \f + \fr 36:21 \ft so there ought to be discretion in words, in choosing a wife, & in all actions, and desires.\f*
\v 22 Aperverse heart will give sorrow, and a cunning man will resist it.
\v 23 Some woman will receive every man: and one daughter is better than another daughter.
\v 24 The beauty of a woman cheereth the face of her husband, and increaseth the desire above all man's concupiscence.
\v 25 If there be a tongue of curing, there is also a mitigating and of mercy: her husband is not according to the sons of men.
\v 26 He that possesseth a good woman beginneth riches: she is an help like unto him, & a pillar as rest. \f + \fr 36:26 \ft In concord small things increase, by discord all things go to havoc.\f*
\v 27 Where there is no hedge, the possession shall be spoiled: and where there is no wife, he mourneth wanting.
\v 28 Who doth credit him that hath no nest, and turning aside wheresoever it waxeth dark, as a robber girded, leaping from city to city.
\c 37
\p
\v 1 Every friend will say: I also have joined friendship: but there is a friend, in name only a friend. Doth there not sorrow remain even to death? \f + \fr 37:1 \ft As friendship is a most necessary thing in human life; so feigned friendship is most dangerous.\f*
\v 2 But a companion and friend will be turned to enmity.
\v 3 O most wicked presumption, whence wast thou created to cover the dry land with malice, and with the deceitfulness thereof?
\v 4 Acompanion is pleasant with his friend in delectations, and in the time of tribulation he will be an adversary.
\v 5 Acompanion is sorry with his friend for his belly's sake, and he will take a shield against the enemy.
\v 6 Forget not thy friend in thy mind, and be not unmindful of him in thy riches.
\v 7 Consult not with him which betrayeth, and hide thy counsel from them that envy thee.
\v 8 Every counseller uttereth counsel, but there is a counseller in himself.
\v 9 From such a counseller keep thy soul. First know what his necessity is: for he will devise to his own mind:
\v 10 lest perhaps he thrust a sharp stake into the ground and say to thee:
\v 11 Thy way is good; and stand over against thee to see what will befall thee.
\v 12 With an irreligious man treat not of holiness, & with the unjust of justice, and with a woman of the thing whereof she is jealous: with a fearful man of war, with a merchant of traffic, with a buyer of selling, with an envious man of giving thanks,
\v 13 with the impious of piety, with the unhonest of honesty, with the field labourer of all work,
\v 14 with him that worketh by the year of the ending of the year, with a slothful servant of much working: attend not to these in all counsel.
\v 15 But be continual with a holy man, whomsoever thou shalt know to observe the fear of God,
\v 16 whose soul is according to thine own soul: and who when thou shalt stumble in the dark, will be sorry for thee.
\v 17 And establish with thyself an heart of good counsel: for there is none other thing more worth to thee than it.
\v 18 The soul of a holy man uttereth sometime true things, more than seven watchmen that sit in a high place to watch.
\v 19 And in all these beseech the Highest, that he direct thy way in truth. \f + \fr 37:19 \ft Man is bound to use all prudent endeavour, & withal most especially to pray for God's direction.\f*
\v 20 Before all works let a true word go before thee, and stable counsel before every act.
\v 21 Awicked word shall change the heart: out of which, rise four parts, good, and evil, life, and death: and the tongue is a continual ruler of them. There is a subtile man teacher of many, & to his own soul he is unprofitable.
\v 22 Acunning man hath taught many, and is sweet to his own soul.
\v 23 He that speaketh sophistically, is odious: in every thing he shall be defrauded.
\v 24 Grace is not given him of our Lord: for he is defrauded of all wisdom.
\v 25 There is a wise man, wise to his own soul: and the fruit of his understanding is laudable.
\v 26 Awise man teacheth his people, and the fruits of his understanding are faithful.
\v 27 Awise man shall be filled with blessings, and they that see will praise him.
\v 28 The life of a man is in the number of days: but the days of Israel are innumerable. \f + \fr 37:28 \ft The days of the Blessed in heaven, who see God, are\f*
\v 29 Awise man in the people shall inherit honour, and his name shall live for ever.
\v 30 Son in thy life prove thy soul: & if it be wicked, give it not power: \f + \fr 37:30 \ft The same which S. Paul admonisheth (1. Cor. 11.) let every one prove himself, by examining & rectifying his conscience.\f* \x + \xo 37:30 \xt 1. Cor. 6.\x*
\v 31 for all things are not expedient for all, and every kind pleaseth not every soul.
\v 32 Be not greedy in all feasting, and pour not out thyself upon all meat:
\v 33 for in many meats there shall be infirmity, and greediness shall approach even to choler.
\v 34 Because of surfeit many have died: but he that is abstinent, shall add life.
\c 38
\p
\v 1 Honour the physician for necessity: for the Highest hath created him. \f + \fr 38:1 \ft Man's body naturally needeth sustenance, & sometimes physic, and so doth his soul; which as it is more excellent, so it ought to be more regarded.\f*
\v 2 For all medicine is of God, & it shall receive gift of the king.
\v 3 The knowledge of the physician shall exalt his head, and in the sight of great men he shall be praised.
\v 4 The Highest hath created medicines of the earth, and a wise man will not abhor them.
\v 5 Was not bitter water made sweet by wood? \x + \xo 38:5 \xt Exo. 15.\x*
\v 6 The virtue of these things is come to the knowledge of men, and the Highest hath given knowledge to men, for to be honoured in his marvelous things.
\v 7 Curing with these things he shall mitigate pain, and the apothecary shall make confections of sweetness, and shall make ointments of health, and his works shall not be consummated.
\v 8 For the peace of God is upon the face of the earth.
\v 9 Son in thine infirmity contemn not thyself, but pray our Lord, and he will cure thee.
\v 10 Turn away from sin, and direct thy hands, and from all offence cleanse thy heart.
\v 11 Give sweetness and a memorial of fine flour, and make a fat oblation, and give place to the physician.
\v 12 For our Lord created him: and let him not depart from thee, because his works be necessary.
\v 13 For there is a time when thou mayst fall into their hands:
\v 14 and they shall beseech our Lord, that he direct their rest, and healing; for their conversation.
\v 15 He that sinneth in his sight, that made him, shall fall into the hands of the physician.
\v 16 Son, upon the dead shed tears, and begin to weep as having suffered doleful things, and according to judgement cover his body, and neglect not his burial.
\v 17 But for detraction bear bitterly the mourning of him one day, and be comforted for the heaviness,
\v 18 and make mourning according to his desert one day, or two, because of detraction.
\v 19 For by heaviness death hasteneth, and it covereth the strength, and sorrow of the heart boweth the neck.
\v 20 In abstraction sorrow is permanent: and the substance of the poor is according to his heart.
\v 21 Give not thine heart into heaviness, but expel it from thee: and remember the latter ends,
\v 22 and forget not: for neither is there return, and him thou shalt profit nothing, and thou shalt hurt thyself.
\v 23 Be mindful of my judgement: for thine also must be so: to me yesterday, and to thee today. \x + \xo 38:23 \xt 2. Reg. 12.\x*
\v 24 In the repose of the dead make the memory of him to rest, and comfort him in the departing of his spirit.
\v 25 The wisdom of a scribe in the time of vacancy: and he that is less in action, shall receive wisdom. \f + \fr 38:25 \ft When pastors have leisure from preaching, they may then profit others by writing. So S. Paul, not only preached,\f*
\v 26 With what wisdom shall he be replenished, that holdeth the plough, and glorieth in the goad, driveth oxen with the prickle, and converseth in their works, and his talk is in the breed of bulls?
\v 27 He will give his heart to turn up furrows, and his watching in the feeding of kine.
\v 28 So every craftsman and workmaster that passeth the night as the day, that maketh graven seals, and his continual diligence varieth the picture: he will give his heart to the similitude of the picture, and his watching will perfect the work.
\v 29 So the ironsmith sitting by the anvil and considering the work of iron. The vapour of the fire will parch his flesh, and he striveth in the heat of the furnace:
\v 30 The noise of the hammer reneweth his ear, and his eye is against the similitude of the vessel.
\v 31 He will give his heart to the finishing of the works, and his watching will polish to perfection.
\v 32 So the potter sitting at his work, turning the wheel with his feet, who is always set in carefulness for his work, and all his working is in number:
\v 33 With his arm he will fashion the clay, and before his feet he will bend his strength:
\v 34 He will give his heart to finish the varnishing thereof, and his watching will make clean the furnace.
\v 35 All these have hoped in their hands, and every one is wise in his own art.
\v 36 Without these a city is not built.
\v 37 And they shall not inhabit, nor walk therein, and they shall not leap high into the congregation.
\v 38 Upon the judge's seat they shall not sit, and the ordinance of judgement they shall not understand, neither shall they declare discipline and judgement, and in parables they shall not be found:
\v 39 but they shall confirm the creature of the world, and their prayer shall be in the work of their art, applying their soul, & searching in the law of the Highest.
\c 39
\p
\v 1 The wise man will search out the wisdom of all the ancients, and will be occupied in the prophets. \f + \fr 39:1 \ft Besides active life commended in the former chap. it is necessary that virtuous men use also meditation & contemplation. Unto which four dispositions are requisite, described in this chap.\f*
\v 2 He will keep the narration of famous men, and will enter withal into the subtilties of parables.
\v 3 He will search out the hidden senses of proverbs, and will converse in the secrets of parables.
\v 4 In the midst of great men he will minister, and in the sight of the president he shall appear.
\v 5 He shall pass into the land of strange nations: for he shall try good and evil in men.
\v 6 He will give his heart to watch early unto our Lord, that made him, and he will pray in the sight of the Highest.
\v 7 He will open his mouth in prayer, and will entreat for his sins.
\v 8 For if it shall please our great Lord, he will fill him with the spirit of understanding: \f + \fr 39:8 \ft 1. (b) True knowledge of holy Mysteries: without the which meditation will be erroneous.\f*
\v 9 and he will pour forth the words of his wisdom as showers, and in prayer will confess to our Lord.
\v 10 And he will direct his counsel, and discipline, and in his secrets he will consult.
\v 11 He will open the discipline of his doctrine, & will glory in the law of the testament of our Lord.
\v 12 Many will praise his wisdom, and it shall not be abolished for ever.
\v 13 The memory of him shall not depart, and his name shall be required from generation to generation.
\v 14 Nations shall declare his wisdom, & the Church will shew forth his praise.
\v 15 If he continue, he shall leave a name more than a thousand: and if he rest, it shall profit him.
\v 16 I will yet consult that I may declare: For as with fury I am replenished.
\v 17 In voice he saith: Hear me ye divine fruits, and as the rose planted upon the rivers of waters fructify ye.
\v 18 As Libanus have ye the odours of sweetness. \f + \fr 39:18 \ft 2. (c) Purity of soul free from grievous sins, and endowed with virtues.\f*
\v 19 Flourish ye flowers, as the lily, and give forth an odour, and bring forth leaves in grace, and praise with song, and bless our Lord in his works.
\v 20 Give magnificence to his name, and confess unto him in the voice of your lips, and in songs of the lips, and harps, & thus shall ye say in confession: \f + \fr 39:20 \ft 3. (d) Humility is especially required in contemplative persons.\f*
\v 21 All the works of our Lord are exceeding good. \x + \xo 39:21 \xt Gen. 1.\x*
\v 22 At his word the water stood as an heap: and at the word of his mouth as it were receptacles of waters: \x + \xo 39:22 \xt Exo. 14.\x*
\v 23 because in his commandment placability is made, and there is no diminishing of his salvation.
\v 24 The works of all flesh are before him, and there is nothing hid from his eyes.
\v 25 From world to world he beholdeth, and nothing is marvelous in his sight.
\v 26 It is not to be said: What is this, or what is that? For all things shall be sought in their time.
\v 27 His blessing hath overflowed as a stream. \f + \fr 39:27 \ft 4. (e) Hope of eternal reward comforteth, & encourageth the servants of God.\f*
\v 28 And as a flood hath watered the dry land, so his wrath shall inherit the nations, that have not sought him: \x + \xo 39:28 \xt Gen. 7.\x*
\v 29 even as he turned waters into drought, & the earth was made dry: and his ways are direct to the ways of them: so to sinners stumbling blocks in his wrath.
\v 30 Good things were created for the good from the beginning, so for the wicked, good things and evil.
\v 31 The beginning of the thing necessary for the life of men, water, fire, and iron, salt, milk, and bread of flour, and honey, and the cluster of grape, and oil, & clothing. \f + \fr 39:31 \ft In the mean time God giveth necessaries for this life. Which the good use rightly to their merit, & the wicked use evil to their damnation.\f*
\v 32 All these shall be converted to saints into good, so also to the impious and to sinners into evil.
\v 33 There are spirits, that were created for vengeance, and in their fury they have confirmed their torments: \f + \fr 39:33 \ft Devils were created in state of grace, & of their own will fell from God, & consequently were punished.\f*
\v 34 in the time of consummation they shall pour out strength: and they shall accomplish the fury of him, that made them.
\v 35 Fire, hail, famine, and death, all these were created for vengeance:
\v 36 the teeth of beasts, and scorpions, and serpents, and sword revenging the impious unto destruction.
\v 37 In his commandments they shall make merry, and on the earth they shall be prepared when need is, and in their times they shall not pretermit a word.
\v 38 Therefore from the beginning I was confirmed, and I have consulted, and thought, and left written.
\v 39 All the works of our Lord are good, & he will give every work in his hour.
\v 40 It is not to be said: This is worse than that: for all shall be approved in their time.
\v 41 And now with all heart and mouth praise ye, and bless the name of our Lord.
\c 40
\p
\v 1 Great travail is created to all men, and an heavy yoke upon the children of Adam, from the day of their coming forth of their mother's womb, until the day of their burying, into the mother of all. \f + \fr 40:1 \ft The penalties which all men even new born infants suffer, do shew that all in general are guilty of original sin, for if they were not guilty, their punishment were not just. That Christ also would be subject to the same penalties was for the sins of others. And though his B. mother was preserved from this sin, yet she was not exempted from the general penalty of all mankind.\f*
\v 2 Their cogitations, and fears of the heart, imagination of things to come, and the day of their ending:
\v 3 from him that sitteth upon the glorious seat, unto him that is humbled in earth & ashes.
\v 4 From him that weareth hyacinth, and beareth the crown, even to him, that is covered with rude linen: fury, envy, tumult, wavering, and the fear of death, anger persevering, and contention,
\v 5 and in the time of repose in bed, the sleep of night changeth his knowledge.
\v 6 Alittle is as nothing in rest, and afterward in sleep, as in the day of watch.
\v 7 He is troubled in the vision of his heart, as he that hath escaped in the day of battle. In the time of his safety he rose up, and marveleth at no fear:
\v 8 With all flesh, from man even to beast, and upon sinners sevenfold.
\v 9 Beside these things, death, blood, contention, and sword, oppressions, famine, and contrition, and scourges:
\v 10 for the wicked all these were created, and for them the flood was made. \x + \xo 40:10 \xt Gen. 7.\x*
\v 11 All things that are of the earth, shall turn into the earth, and all waters shall return into the sea. \x + \xo 40:11 \xt Eccle. 1.\x*
\v 12 All bribing, and iniquity shall be clean taken away, and fidelity shall stand for ever.
\v 13 The riches of the unjust shall be dried up as a river, and they shall sound as great thunder in rain.
\v 14 In opening his hands he shall rejoice: so transgressors shall pine away in consumption.
\v 15 The nephews of the impious shall not multiply boughs, nor unclean roots sound upon the top of a rock.
\v 16 Over all water greenness, and at the brink of the river it shall be plucked up before all grass.
\v 17 Grace is as paradise in blessings, and mercy remaineth for ever.
\v 18 The life of a workman that is sufficient for himself shall be sweet, and in it thou shalt find a treasure.
\v 19 Children, and building of a city shall confirm the name, and an unspotted woman shall be counted above this.
\v 20 Wine and music make a joyful heart: and the love of wisdom is above both.
\v 21 Shalms, and Psaltery make sweet melody, and a sweet tongue is above both.
\v 22 Thine eye will desire grace and beauty, and green sown fields are above this. \f + \fr 40:22 \ft The society of Christ's Church flourishing in all virtues excelleth the benefits of the old Testament.\f*
\v 23 Afriend and companion meeting together in time, & above them both is a woman with her husband.
\v 24 Brethren are an help in the time of tribulation, and mercy shall deliver more than they.
\v 25 Gold & silver are the establishing of the feet: and counsel is well accepted above them both.
\v 26 Riches & strength exalt the heart, and above these is the fear of our Lord.
\v 27 There is no diminution in the fear of our Lord, and in it there is no need to seek for help.
\v 28 The fear of our Lord is as a paradise of blessing, and they have covered it above all glory.
\v 29 Son in thy lifetime want not: for it is better to die than to want. \f + \fr 40:29 \ft Every one is bound to labour that he want not necessaries.\f*
\v 30 Aman that looketh toward another man's table, his life is as no life, thinking how to live, for he feedeth his soul with another man's meats.
\v 31 But a man nurtured and taught, will look to himself.
\v 32 Poverty will be sweet in the mouth of the unwise, and in his belly a fire will burn.
\c 41
\p
\v 1 O Death how bitter is thy memory to a man that hath peace in his riches:
\v 2 to a man that is at rest, and whose ways are prosperous in all things, and that is yet able to take meat!
\v 3 O death, thy judgement is good to a needy man, and him that is diminished in strength,
\v 4 and faileth in age, and that is careful of all things, and to the incredulous, that loseth patience!
\v 5 Fear not the judgement of death. Remember what things have been before thee, and what come after thee: this is the judgement from our Lord to all flesh:
\v 6 and what shall come upon thee by the good pleasure of the Highest? Whether it be ten, or an hundred, or a thousand years.
\v 7 For in hell there is no accusing of life. \f + \fr 41:7 \ft It is to no purpose after death to accuse the shortness, or length of life, pretending the same to have been cause of sin. For God doth all justly, yea and for the best, if men would so use his benefits.\f*
\v 8 The children of sinners become children of abominations, and they that converse near the houses of the impious.
\v 9 The inheritance of the children of sinners shall perish, and with their seed shall be continuance of reproach.
\v 10 The children complain of an impious father, because for him they are in reproach.
\v 11 Woe to you ye impious men, which have forsaken the law of our Lord the Highest.
\v 12 And if ye be born, ye shall be born in malediction: and if ye die, in malediction shall be your portion.
\v 13 All things that are of the earth, shall return into the earth: so the impious from malediction to perdition.
\v 14 The mourning of men is in their body, but the name of the impious shall be clean wiped out.
\v 15 Have care of a good name: for this shall be more permanent to thee than a thousand treasures precious and great.
\v 16 There is a number of the days of a good life: but a good name shall continue for ever.
\v 17 Children, keep ye discipline in peace. For wisdom hid, and treasure not seen, what profit is there in them both?
\v 18 Better is the man that hideth his folly, than the man that hideth his wisdom.
\v 19 But yet have reverence to these things, which proceed from my mouth. \f + \fr 41:19 \ft It behoveth children, and scholers to esteem that which their elders teach:\f*
\v 20 For it is not good to observe all shamefastness: & all things do not please all men in opinion. \f + \fr 41:20 \ft though the same doth not seem reasonable in their own opinion.\f*
\v 21 Be ashamed before father & before mother, of fornication: and before the president and before the mighty, of lying:
\v 22 before the Prince, and before the judge, of offence: before the synagogue and the people, of iniquity:
\v 23 before companion and friend, of injustice: and before the place where thou dwellest,
\v 24 of theft, of the truth of God, and his testament: of leaning on the bread, and of reproof for the thing given and taken:
\v 25 before them that salute thee, of silence: of beholding a woman that is an harlot: and of turning away thy countenance from thy kinsman.
\v 26 Turn not away thy face from thy neighbour, & of taking away part & not restoring.
\v 27 Behold not another man's wife, and search not his handmaid, neither stand by her bed. \x + \xo 41:27 \xt Mat. 5. v. 28.\x*
\v 28 Before friends, of opprobrious words: and when thou hast given, upbraid not.
\c 42
\p
\v 1 Repeat not the word which thou hast heard, neither reveal thou of a secret word, & thou shalt indeed be without confusion, and shalt find grace in the sight of all men: be not ashamed for all these things, and accept not person thereby to sin. \f + \fr 42:1 \ft It is not lawful to reveal that, which we justly promise to conceal.\f* \x + \xo 42:1 \xt Levit. 19. Deu. 1. 16. Pro. 24. Iacob. 2.\x*
\v 2 Of the law of the Highest, and his testament, and of judgement to justify the impious,
\v 3 of the word of companions and wayfaring men, and of the giving of the inheritance of friends,
\v 4 of the equality of balance and weights, of the getting of many things and few,
\v 5 of the corruption of buying, and of merchants, and of much discipline of thy children, and to make bloody the side of a wicked servant.
\v 6 Over a naughty woman a seal is good.
\v 7 Where there are many hands, shut up, and what soever thou shalt deliver, number, and weigh it: and write every thing given and received.
\v 8 Of the discipline of the unwise and foolish, and of ancients, that are judged of young men: and thou shalt be well instructed in all things, and approved in the sight of all the living.
\v 9 Adaughter is the secret watch of the father, and the care of her taketh away sleep, lest perhaps in her youth she become past age, & abiding with an husband she become odious:
\v 10 lest at any time she be corrupted in her virginity, and in her father's house she be found with child: lest perhaps abiding with her husband she transgress, or at the least become barren.
\v 11 Over a dissolute daughter keep sure watch: lest at any time she make thee come into reproach with thine enemies, because of detraction in the city, and the objection of the people, and she confound thee in the multitude of the people.
\v 12 Look not on every body for beauty sake: & among women tarry not.
\v 13 For out of garments cometh forth the moth, and from a woman the iniquity of a man.
\v 14 For better is the iniquity of a man, than a woman doing a good turn, and a woman shaming unto reproach. \f + \fr 42:14 \ft There is less danger in conversing familiarly with a wicked man, than with a friendly woman. In which conversation, much prudence is required, as is before admonished. chap. 9.\f*
\v 15 Itherefore will be mindful of the works of our Lord, and I will shew forth which I have seen. By the words of our Lord are his works.
\v 16 The sun illuminating hath looked throughout all, and full of the glory of our Lord is his work.
\v 17 Hath not our Lord made the saints to declare all his marvelous things, which our Lord the omnipotent confirmed to be established in his glory?
\v 18 He hath searched out the depth, and the heart of men: & in their subtility he hath considered.
\v 19 For our Lord hath known all knowledge, and hath beheld the sign of age, declaring what things are past, and what are to come, revealing the tokens of secret things. \f + \fr 42:19 \ft The excellency of God, which cannot be seen with mortal eye (Exo. 33.) is proposed to our meditation in his works. The like in, Iob. 38. 39. 40. 41. and in many places of holy Scripture.\f*
\v 20 No cogitation escapeth him, and no word hideth itself from him.
\v 21 The glorious works of his wisdom he hath beautified: who is before the world & world without end, neither is there added,
\v 22 nor diminished, and he needeth not any man's counsel.
\v 23 How are all his works to be desired, and which is as it were a spark to consider!
\v 24 All these live, and remain for ever, and in all necessity all things obey him.
\v 25 All things double, one against one, and he hath made nothing to want.
\v 26 He hath confirmed the good things of every one. And who shall be filled seeing his glory?
\c 43
\p
\v 1 The firmament of height is his beauty, the beauty of heaven is in the vision of glory.
\v 2 The sun in sight declaring at his coming forth, a marvelous instrument, the work of the Highest. \f + \fr 43:2 \ft Of all senseless creatures, yea & of sensible also, that have not reason, the sun is most excellent. Of which all corporal creatures receive their light: & by whose influence all generation of creatures proceedeth: whereof is this Maxim in Philosophy, that The sun and man beget a man. And Aristotel calleth the sun the father of men and of gods.\f*
\v 3 At noon it burneth the earth, and who can abide in the presence of the heat thereof: keeping a furnace in the works of heat:
\v 4 the sun three times so much burning the mountains, casting out fiery beams, and shining with his beams blindeth the eyes.
\v 5 Great is our Lord that made it, and by his words it hath hastened his course.
\v 6 And the moon in all in her time, is the shewing of season and the sign of age.
\v 7 By the moon is the sign of a festival day, a light that diminisheth in consummation.
\v 8 The month is according to her name, increasing marvelously in consummation.
\v 9 An instrument of the camp on high, shining gloriously in the firmament of heaven.
\v 10 The glory of the stars is the beauty of heaven, our Lord illuminating the world on high.
\v 11 In the words of the holy one they shall stand to judgement, and shall not fail in their watches.
\v 12 See the bow, and bless him that made it: it is very beautiful in his brightness.
\v 13 It hath compassed heaven in the circuit of his glory, the hands of the Highest have opened it.
\v 14 But by his commandment he hath hastened snow, & he hasteth to send forth the lightnings of his judgement.
\v 15 Therefore are the treasures opened, & the clouds fly forth as birds.
\v 16 By his greatness he hath set the clouds, & the hailstones are broken.
\v 17 In his sight the mountains shall be moved, & at his will the south wind hath blown.
\v 18 The noise of his thunder shall beat the earth, the tempest of the northwind, and the gathering together of wind:
\v 19 and as the bird lighting down to sit, he scattereth snow, and the falling thereof, is as the locust diving downward.
\v 20 The eye shall admire the beauty of the whiteness thereof, and the heart quaketh at the shower thereof. \f + \fr 43:20 \ft Which also appeareth even in the least creatures, whose natural substances & qualities, with other accidents, the more any man considereth the more he shall admire God, the only Creator of all.\f*
\v 21 He shall pour out frost upon the earth as salt: and when it freezeth, it shall be made as the tops of a thistle.
\v 22 The cold north wind blew, & of water there froze crystal, upon all gathering together of waters it shall rest, & as a breast plate it shall put itself upon the waters.
\v 23 And it shall devour the mountains, & burn the desert, & extinguish that which is green as fire.
\v 24 The remedy of all is in the hasty coming of a cloud, and a dew meeting it by the heat that cometh, shall make it quail.
\v 25 At his word the wind was still, and with his thought he appeased the depth, and our Lord planted Islands therein.
\v 26 They that sail on the sea, tell the perils thereof: & hearing with our ears we shall marvel.
\v 27 There are goodly works, & marvelous: diverse kinds of beasts, & of all cattle, & the creature of mighty beasts.
\v 28 Through him is the end of their journey confirmed, and by his word all things are set in order.
\v 29 We shall say many things, & shall fail in words; but the sum of our words is, He is in all.
\v 30 Glorifying him how far shall we be able? For the omnipotent himself is above all his works.
\v 31 Our Lord is terrible, & exceeding great, & his might is marvelous.
\v 32 Glorifying our Lord as much as ever you can, he shall yet surpass, and his magnificence is marvelous.
\v 33 Blessing our Lord, exalt him as much as you can: for he is greater than all praise.
\v 34 Exalting him be ye replenished with strength. Labour not: for you shall not comprehend.
\v 35 Who shall see him, and shall declare him? And who shall magnify him as he is from the beginning?
\v 36 Many things hid are greater than these: for we have seen few of his works.
\v 37 But our Lord made all things, and to them that live piously he hath given wisdom.
\c 44
\p
\v 1 Let us praise glorious men, and our fathers in their generation.
\v 2 Much glory hath our Lord made by his magnificence from the beginning of the world.
\v 3 Ruling in their dominions, men great for force, and endued with their wisdom, declaring in the prophets the dignity of prophets, \f + \fr 44:3 \ft Virtuous men are rightly called Lords, and Princes; so the children of Heth said to Abraham. My Lord, thou art a prince of God among us. Gen. 23.\f*
\v 4 and ruling in the people that was present, and by the virtue of wisdom most holy words to the peoples.
\v 5 In their skill seeking out musical melodies, & uttering songs of scriptures.
\v 6 Rich men in force studying beautifulness: living at peace in their houses.
\v 7 All these in the generations of their nation have obtained glory, and in their days are praised.
\v 8 They that were born of them have left a name to tell their praises:
\v 9 and there are some of whom there is no memory: they are perished, as they that never were; & are born, as not born at all, & their children with them.
\v 10 But they are men of mercy, whose godly deeds have not failed:
\v 11 good things continue with their seed,
\v 12 their nephews are an holy inheritance, and their seed hath stood in the testaments:
\v 13 and their children because of them abide for ever: their seed and their glory shall not be forsaken.
\v 14 Their bodies are buried in peace, and their name liveth unto generation and generation.
\v 15 Let peoples tell their wisdom, and the Church declare their praise. \f + \fr 44:15 \ft Enoch shall preach penance in the time of Antichrist.\f*
\v 16 Henoch pleased God, and was translated into paradise, that he may give repentance to the nations.
\v 17 Noe was found perfect, just, and in the time of wrath he was made a reconciliation.
\v 18 Therefore was there a remnant left to the earth, when the flood was made.
\v 19 The testaments of the world were made with him, that all flesh should no more be destroyed with the flood.
\v 20 Abraham the great father of the multitude of the nations, and there was not found the like to him in glory, who kept the law of the Highest, and was in covenant with him.
\v 21 In his flesh he made the covenant to stand, and in tentation he was found faithful.
\v 22 Therefore by an oath he gave him glory in his nation, that he should increase as an heap of earth, \x + \xo 44:22 \xt Gen. 22. Heb. 11.\x*
\v 23 and that he would exalt his seed as the stars, and they should inherit from sea to sea, and from the river to the ends of the earth.
\v 24 And he did in like manner in Isaac for Abraham his father.
\v 25 Our Lord gave him the blessing of all nations, and confirmed his covenant upon the head of Jacob. \f + \fr 44:25 \ft Isaac and Jacob were blessed in Abraham.\f*
\v 26 He knew him in his blessings, and gave him an inheritance, & divided him his portion in twelve tribes.
\v 27 And he preserved unto him men of mercy, and found grace in the eyes of all flesh.
\c 45
\p
\v 1 Moyses beloved of God, and men: whose memory is in benediction. \x + \xo 45:1 \xt Exo. 3.\x*
\v 2 He made him like in the glory of saints, and magnified him in the fear of his enemies. And with his words he appeased monsters.
\v 3 He glorified him in the sight of kings, and gave him commandment before his people, & shewed him his glory.
\v 4 In his faith and meekness he made him holy, and chose him of all flesh.
\v 5 For he heard him, and his voice, and brought him into a cloud. \x + \xo 45:5 \xt Num. 21.\x*
\v 6 And he gave him precepts face to face, and a law of life and discipline, to teach Jacob his testament, and Israel his judgements. \f + \fr 45:6 \ft Moyses saw God's works more clearly than other Prophets, yet saw not his substance, as is noted Exod. 33.\f*
\v 7 He exalted Aaron his brother high, and like to himself of the tribe of Levi. \x + \xo 45:7 \xt Exo. 28.\x*
\v 8 He established unto him an everlasting testament, and gave him the Priesthood of the nation, and made him blessed in glory, \f + \fr 45:8 \ft Aaron's priesthood continued so long as Moyses' law: that was till Christ. And now the priesthood according to the order of Melchisedech continueth to the end of the world.\f*
\v 9 and he girded him about with a girdle, and put upon him a robe of glory, and crowned him in furniture of power.
\v 10 Garments to the feet, and breeches, and an Ephod he put upon him, and compassed him with little bells of gold very many round about,
\v 11 to give a sound in his going, to make sound heard in the temple for a memory to the children of his nation.
\v 12 An holy robe, of gold, and hyacinth, and purple, a woven work, of a wiseman, endued with judgement and truth:
\v 13 Of twisted scarlet the work of an artificer, with precious stones figured in the closure of gold, and graven by the work of a lapidary for a memorial, according to the number of the tribes of Israel.
\v 14 Acrown of gold upon his mitre graven with a seal of holiness, and the glory of honour: a work of power, & the adorned desires of the eyes.
\v 15 There were none such so fair before him, even from the beginning.
\v 16 No stranger was clothed with them, but only his children alone, and his nephews for ever.
\v 17 His sacrifices were consumed with fire every day. \x + \xo 45:17 \xt Lev. 8.\x*
\v 18 Moyses filled his hands, & anointed him with holy oil.
\v 19 It was made unto him for an everlasting testament, and to his seed as the days of heaven, to do the function of Priesthood, and to have praise and to glorify his people in his name.
\v 20 He chose him of all that lived, to offer sacrifice to God, incense, and good odour, for a memorial to pacify for his people:
\v 21 and he gave them power in his precepts, in the testaments of his judgements, to teach Jacob his testimonies, and in his law to give light to Israel.
\v 22 Because strangers stood against him, and for envy men compassed him about in the desert, they that were with Dathan and Abiron, and the congregation of Core in anger. \x + \xo 45:22 \xt Num. 16.\x*
\v 23 Our Lord God saw, and it please him not, and they were consumed in the violence of wrath.
\v 24 He did prodigious things unto them, and consumed them in flame of fire.
\v 25 And he added glory to Aaron, and gave him an inheritance, and divided unto him the first fruits of the increase of the earth.
\v 26 He prepared them bread in the first unto satiety: for the sacrifices also of our Lord they shall eat, which he gave to him, and to his seed.
\v 27 But he shall not inherit the nations in the land, and he hath no part in the nation: for himself is his portion & inheritance. \f + \fr 45:27 \ft The tribe of Levi had not a portion of inheritance separate from the rest, but had tithes, first fruits, and oblations for their temporal provision.\f*
\v 28 Phinees the son of Eleazar is the third in glory, in imitating him in the fear of our Lord: \x + \xo 45:28 \xt Nu. 25.\x*
\v 29 and to stand in the reverence of the nation: in the goodness and alacrity of his soul he pacified God for Israel.
\v 30 Therefore did he establish unto him a covenant of peace, to be the Prince of the holies, and to his nation, that the dignity of Priesthood should be to him and to his seed for ever.
\v 31 And the testament to David king, the son of Jesse of the tribe of Juda, and inheritance to him and to his seed, that he might give wisdom into our heart to judge his nation in justice, that their good things might not be abolished, & their glory in their nation he made everlasting. \f + \fr 45:31 \ft King David gave special assistance to the Priests, and greatly advanced God's service 1. Paral. 23. &c.\f*
\c 46
\p
\v 1 Strong in battle was Jesus the son of Nave, successor of Moyses among the prophets, who was great according to his name, \f + \fr 46:1 \ft Iosue succeeded in the temporal government: for the spiritual pertained to the successors of Aaron. Num. 27.\f*
\v 2 most great in the salvation of God's elect, to overthrow the enemies rising up, that he might get the inheritance of Israel.
\v 3 What glory obtained he in lifting up his hands, and casting swords against the cities?
\v 4 Who before him did so resist? For our Lord himself brought the enemies.
\v 5 Whether was not the sun hindered in his anger, and one day was made as two? \x + \xo 46:5 \xt Iosue 10.\x*
\v 6 He invocated the mighty sovereign in assaulting of the enemies on every side, and the great and holy God heard him in hail-stones of exceeding great force.
\v 7 He made violent assault against the nation of his enemies, and in the going down he destroyed the adversaries,
\v 8 that the nations might know his might, that it is not easy to fight against God. And he followed at the back of the mighty.
\v 9 And in the days of Moyses did mercy, and Caleb the son of Jephone, did stand against the enemy, and stayed the nation from sins, and appeased the murmuring of malice. \f + \fr 46:9 \ft Only Iosue and Caleb remained of those which came out of Ægypt, all the rest died in the desert; and their children entered into Chanaan. Num. 14.\f* \x + \xo 46:9 \xt Nu. 14.\x*
\v 10 And they two being appointed, were delivered out of danger from among the number of six hundred thousand foot men, to bring them into their inheritance, into the land that yieldeth milk and honey.
\v 11 And our Lord gave strength to Caleb himself, and his strength continued even until old age, so that he went up into the high place of the land, & his seed obtained inheritance. \x + \xo 46:11 \xt Iosue 14.\x*
\v 12 That all the children of Israel might see, that it is good to obey the holy God.
\v 13 And all the judges by their name, whose heart was not corrupted: which were not turned away from our Lord, \f + \fr 46:13 \ft Though some of the Judges were sometimes great sinners, yet they were finally just, & for their good acts much renowned.\f*
\v 14 that their memory might be blessed, and their bones spring out of their place, \x + \xo 46:14 \xt 1. Reg. 17.\x*
\v 15 and their name continue for ever, the glory of the holy men remaining unto their children.
\v 16 The beloved of our Lord his God Samuel the prophet of our Lord, renewed the empire, and anointed princes in his nation. \f + \fr 46:16 \ft Samuel anointed Saul and David Kings.\f*
\v 17 By the law of our Lord he judged the congregation, and the God of Jacob saw, and in his fidelity was proved a prophet.
\v 18 And he was known faithful in his words, because he saw the God of light:
\v 19 and invocated our Lord Omnipotent, in assaulting the enemies besetting him on every side, in the oblation of an immaculate lamb.
\v 20 And our Lord thundered from heaven, and in great sound he made his voice heard, \x + \xo 46:20 \xt 1. Reg. 7.\x*
\v 21 and he discomfited the Princes of the Tyrians, and all the dukes of the Philisthiims:
\v 22 and before the time of the end of his life, and the world, he gave testimony before our Lord, and his Christ, money and what soever besides unto the very shoes he took not of all flesh, and no man accused him. \x + \xo 46:22 \xt 1. Reg. 12.\x*
\v 23 And after this he slept, and he notified to the king, and shewed him the end of his life, and he exalted his voice out of the earth in prophecy, to take clean away the impiety of the nation.
\c 47
\p
\v 1 After these things arose Nathan the Prophet in the days of David. \x + \xo 47:1 \xt 2. Reg. 11.\x*
\v 2 And as the fat separated from the flesh, so was David from the children of Israel.
\v 3 He played with lions as it were with lambs: and with bears he did in like manner as with lambs of sheep in his youth. \x + \xo 47:3 \xt 1. Reg. 17.\x*
\v 4 Did not he kill the giant, & took away reproach from his nation? \f + \fr 47:4 \ft Ibidem.\f*
\v 5 In lifting up his hand, with a stone of the sling he overthrew the boasting of Goliath:
\v 6 for he invocated our Lord the omnipotent, and he gave in his right hand, to take away the man strong in battle, and to exalt the horn of his nation.
\v 7 So in ten thousand did he glorify him, and praised him in the blessings of our Lord, in offering to him a crown of glory: \x + \xo 47:7 \xt 1. Reg. 18.\x*
\v 8 for he destroyed the enemies on every side, and rooted out the Philisthiims the adversaries even until this present day: he brake their horn for ever.
\v 9 In every work he gave confession to the Holy one, and to the Highest, in the word of glory.
\v 10 From all his heart he praised our Lord, & loved God, that made him, and gave him might against his enemies: \f + \fr 47:10 \ft Amongst all the renowned acts of David his pure and sincere heart most pleased God.\f*
\v 11 and he made singers to stand before the altar, and by their sound he made sweet tunes. \x + \xo 47:11 \xt 1. Par. 25.\x*
\v 12 And in the solemnities he gave honour, and adorned the times even to the end of his life, that they should praise the holy name of our Lord, and magnify the holiness of God in the morning.
\v 13 Our Lord purged his sins, and exalted his horn for ever: and he gave him a testament of the kingdom, and the seat of glory in Israel. \x + \xo 47:13 \xt 2. Reg. 12.\x*
\v 14 After him arose a wise son, and for him did he overthrow all the might of the enemies. \f + \fr 47:14 \ft For David's sake God gave wisdom to Salomon, and peace in his kingdom.\f*
\v 15 Salomon reigned in days of peace, to whom God subdued all his enemies, that he might build an house in his name, & prepare holiness for ever: as thou art instructed in thy youth. \f + \fr 47:15 \ft By Apostrophe the author turneth his speech to Salomon.\f* \x + \xo 47:15 \xt 3. Reg. 3.\x* \x + \xo 47:15 \xt 3. Reg. 4.\x*
\v 16 And thou art replenished as a river with wisdom, and thy soul discovered the earth.
\v 17 And thou didst multiply dark sayings in comparisons: thy name was bruited to the islands far off, and thou wast beloved in thy peace.
\v 18 The lands marveled at the songs and proverbs, and comparisons, and interpretations,
\v 19 and at the name of our Lord God, whose name is, God of Israel.
\v 20 Thou didst gather gold as copper, and filledst silver as lead, \x + \xo 47:20 \xt 3. Reg. 10.\x*
\v 21 and bowedst thy thighs to women: thou hast had power on thy body.
\v 22 Thou hast made a blot in thy glory, & profaned thy seed to bring wrath to thy children, & thy folly to be kindled,
\v 23 to make the Kingdom divided, and a stubborn kingdom to reign of Ephraim.
\v 24 But God will not leave his mercy, and he will not corrupt, nor abolish his own works, neither will he destroy from the stock the nephews of his elect: and he will not corrupt the seed of him, that loveth our Lord. \x + \xo 47:24 \xt Psa. 88. v. 34.\x*
\v 25 But he gave a remnant to Jacob, and to David of the same stock.
\v 26 And Salomon had an end with his fathers.
\v 27 And he left after him of his seed, the folly of the nation,
\v 28 and Roboam having little wisdom, who turned away the nation by his counsel, \x + \xo 47:28 \xt 3. Reg. 12.\x*
\v 29 and Jeroboam the son of Nabat, who made Israel to sin, and made a way of sinning to Ephraim, and their sins did abound very many.
\v 30 They removed them away from their land very far.
\v 31 And he sought all iniquities, till there came defence unto them, and he rid them from all sins.
\c 48
\p
\v 1 And there arose Elias the prophet, as it were fire, and his word burnt as a little torch.
\v 2 Who brought famine upon them, and they provoking him in their envy were made few, for they could not abide the precepts of our Lord. \x + \xo 48:2 \xt 3. Reg. 17.\x*
\v 3 By the word of our Lord he stayed heaven, and he brought down fire from heaven thrice. \f + \fr 48:3 \ft Elias procured fire from heaven to burn his sacrifice, 3. Reg. 18. and twice more to burn an hundred men which persecuted him. 4. Reg. 1.\f*
\v 4 So was Elias magnified in his marvelous works. And who can so glory like unto thee?
\v 5 Who didst raise up the dead from hell, from the lot of death, in the word of our Lord God.
\v 6 Who didst cast down kings to destruction, and didst easily break their might, and the glorious from their bed.
\v 7 Who hearest judgement in Sina, and in Horeb judgements of defence.
\v 8 Who anointest kings to repentance, and makest Prophets successors after thee. \x + \xo 48:8 \xt 3. Reg. 9.\x*
\v 9 Who wast received in a whirlwind of fire, in a chariot of fiery horses. \x + \xo 48:9 \xt 4. Reg. 2.\x*
\v 10 Who art written in the judgements of times, to appease the wrath of our Lord, to reconcile the heart of the father to the son, and to restore the tribes of Jacob.
\v 11 Blessed are they that saw thee, and were honoured in thy friendship.
\v 12 For we live by life only, but after death our name shall not be such.
\v 13 Elias was indeed hid in the whirlwind, & his spirit was complete in Eliseus: in his days he feared not the Prince, and no man overcame him by might.
\v 14 Neither did any word overcome him, and his body prophesied being dead.
\v 15 In his life he did wonders, and in death he wrought marvelous things.
\v 16 In all these things the people repented not, and they departed not from their sins, till they were cast out of their land, and were dispersed into all the earth.
\v 17 And there was left a very small nation, and a Prince in the house of David.
\v 18 Some of them did that which pleased God: but others committed many sins.
\v 19 Ezechias fenced his city, and brought in water into the midst thereof, and digged a rock with iron, and built a well for water. \x + \xo 48:19 \xt 4. Reg. 20.\x*
\v 20 In his days came up Sennacherib, and sent Rabsaces, and lifted up his hand against them, and put forth his hand upon Sion, and became proud by his mightiness. \x + \xo 48:20 \xt 4. Reg. 18.\x*
\v 21 Then were their hearts and hands moved: and they were in sorrow as travailing women.
\v 22 And they invocated our merciful Lord, and spreading their hands, they lifted them up to heaven, and the holy Lord God quickly heard their voice. \f + \fr 48:22 \ft Prayer prevailed, when forces were not sufficient. See. 4. Reg. 19.\f*
\v 23 He was not mindful of their sins, neither did he give them to their enemies, but purged them by the hand of Isaie the holy Prophet. \x + \xo 48:23 \xt 4. Reg. 19.\x*
\v 24 He overthrew the camp of the Assyrians, and the Angel of our Lord destroyed them. \x + \xo 48:24 \xt Isa. 37.\x*
\v 25 For Ezechias did that which pleased God, and went strongly in the way of David his father, which Isaie commanded him, the great prophet, and faithful in the sight of God.
\v 26 In his days the sun returned backward, & added life to the king. \x + \xo 48:26 \xt 4. Reg. 20. Isa. 38.\x*
\v 27 By a great spirit he saw the last things, and comforted the mourners in Sion.
\v 28 For ever he shewed the things to come, & secret things before they came to pass.
\c 49
\p
\v 1 The memory of Josias is according to the confection of perfume made by the work of an apothecary. \x + \xo 49:1 \xt 4. Reg. 22.\x*
\v 2 His remembrance shall be sweet as honey in every mouth, & as music in a banquet of wine.
\v 3 He was directed by God into the repentance of the nation, and he took away the abominations of impiety. \x + \xo 49:3 \xt 2. Par. 34.\x*
\v 4 And he governed his heart toward our Lord, and in the days of sinners he strengthened piety. \x + \xo 49:4 \xt 4. Reg. 13.\x*
\v 5 Except David, and Ezechias, and Josias, all committed sin. \f + \fr 49:5 \ft Many other Kings of Juda refrained always from committing idolatry, but these three destroyed all places of idolatry in their kingdom, which the others did not.\f*
\v 6 For the kings of Juda forsook the law of the Highest, and contemned the fear of God.
\v 7 For they gave their kingdom to others and their glory to a strange nation.
\v 8 They burnt the chosen city of holiness, & made the ways thereof desolate in the hand of Jeremie. \x + \xo 49:8 \xt 4. Reg. 25.\x*
\v 9 For they evil entreated him, who was consecrated a prophet from his mother's womb, to overthrow, & pluck up, and destroy, and to build again, and renew. \x + \xo 49:9 \xt Iere. 1.\x*
\v 10 Ezechiel who saw the sight of glory, which he shewed him in the chariot of Cherubs. \x + \xo 49:10 \xt Ezec. 1.\x*
\v 11 For he made mention of the enemies in rain, to do good unto them, that have shewed right ways.
\v 12 And the bones of the twelve prophets well may they spring out of their place: for they have strengthened Jacob, and have redeemed themselves in the fidelity of power.
\v 13 How may we magnify Zorobabel? For he also was as a signet on the right hand, \x + \xo 49:13 \xt Agge. 2.\x*
\v 14 and so Jesus the son of Josedec: who in their days built the house, and erected the holy temple to our Lord, prepared to everlasting glory. \x + \xo 49:14 \xt 1. Esd. 3. 3. Esd. 5. Zach. 3.\x*
\v 15 And Nehemias in the memory of much time, who erected us our walls overthrown, and set up the gates and locks, who built our houses. \x + \xo 49:15 \xt 2. Esd. 2.\x*
\v 16 No man hath been born in the earth like to Henoch: for he also was taken up from the earth.
\v 17 Neither as Joseph, who was a man born Prince of his brethren, the stay of the nation, the ruler of his brethren, the stay of the people: \x + \xo 49:17 \xt Gen. 39. 40 &c.\x*
\v 18 and his bones were visited, and after death they prophesied. \f + \fr 49:18 \ft Ioseph prophesying that the people should depart from Ægypt, willed them to carry his bones with them. Gen. 50. So by carrying his bones they professed, that he had truly prophesied.\f*
\v 19 Seth, and Sem obtained glory with men: and above every soul, in the beginning Adam.
\c 50
\p
\v 1 Simon the son of Onias, the high priest, who in his life held up the house, and in his days strengthened the temple.
\v 2 The height also of the temple was founded by him, the double building and high walls of the temple.
\v 3 In his days the wells of waters flowed out, and they were filled as the sea above measure.
\v 4 Who had care of his nation, and delivered it from perdition.
\v 5 Who prevailed to amplify the city, who obtained glory in conversing with the nation: and amplified the entrance of the house, and the court.
\v 6 As the morning star in the midst of a cloud, and as the full moon he shineth in his days.
\v 7 And as the sun shining, so did he shine in the temple of God.
\v 8 As the rainbow that shineth among the clouds of glory, and as a flower of roses in the days of the spring, and as the lilies that are in the passage of water, and as frankincense smelling in summer days.
\v 9 As fire glistering, and frankincense burning in the fire.
\v 10 As a massy vessel of gold, adorned with every precious stone.
\v 11 As an olive tree budding, and a cypress tree advancing itself on high, when he took the robe of glory, and was revested to the consummation of strength.
\v 12 In going up to the holy altar, he made the vesture of holiness, glory.
\v 13 And in receiving the portions out of the hand of the Priests, himself also standing by the altar. About him was the ring of his brethren: and as the cedar plant in mount Libanus,
\v 14 so stood they about him as boughs of the palm tree, & all the children of Aaron in their glory.
\v 15 And the oblation of our Lord in their hands, before all the synagogue of Israel: and executing the consummation on the altar, to amplify the oblation of the high King,
\v 16 he stretched forth his hand in oblation of moist sacrifice, and offered of the blood of the grape. \f + \fr 50:16 \ft * Libatione.\f*
\v 17 He poured out on the foundation of the altar a divine odour to the high Prince.
\v 18 Then cried out the children of Aaron, they sounded with beaten trumpets, and made a great voice to be heard for a remembrance before God.
\v 19 Then all the people together made haste, and fell on their face upon the earth, to adore our Lord their God, and to make prayers to God Omnipotent the Highest.
\v 20 And the singers amplified in their voices, and in the great house the sound was increased full of sweetness.
\v 21 And the people in prayer desired our Lord the Highest, until the honour of our Lord was perfected, and they finished their office.
\v 22 Then coming down, he lifted up his hands over all the congregation of the children of Israel, to give glory to God from his lips, and to glory in his name, \x + \xo 50:22 \xt Num. 6. v. 23.\x*
\v 23 and he repeated his prayer, willing to shew the power of God.
\v 24 And now pray ye the God of all, who hath done great things in all the land, who hath increased our days from our mother's womb, and hath done with us according to his mercy:
\v 25 give he unto us joyfulness of heart everlasting:
\v 26 that Israel may believe that the mercy of God is with us, to deliver us in his days.
\v 27 Two nations my soul hateth: and the third is no nation, which I hate: \f + \fr 50:27 \ft Three nations; the Idumeans, Philistiims, and Samaritanes, did most persecute the Israelites: the Samaritanes were no one pure nation, but mixt of Assirians and Jews: and so here called no nation.\f*
\v 28 they that sit in mount Seir, and the Philisthiims, and the foolish people that dwell in Sichem. \f + \fr 50:28 \ft They are also called a foolish people, because they knowing true religion, mixed idolatry therewith, according to diverse sects, as appeareth 4. Reg. 17. v. 29.\f*
\v 29 Jesus the son of Sirach, a man of Jerusalem, wrote the doctrine of wisdom and discipline in this book, who renewed wisdom from his heart.
\v 30 Blessed is he, that converseth in these good things: and he that layeth them in his heart, shall be wise always.
\v 31 For if he do them, he shall be able to do all things: because his steps are in the light of God.
\c 51
\p
\v 1 The prayer of Jesus the son of Sirach. I will confess to thee o Lord King, and will praise thee God my Savior. \f + \fr 51:1 \ft Where we are not able to render recompence to benefactors; especially to God, we are the more bound to acknowledge his many great benefits, altogether undeserved by us.\f*
\v 2 I will confess to thy name: because thou art become my helper and protector,
\v 3 & hast delivered my body from perdition, from the snare of an unjust tongue, and from the lips of them that work lying, and in the sight of them that stood up thou art become my helper.
\v 4 And thou hast delivered me according to the multitude of the mercy of thy name from them that did roar, prepared to devour,
\v 5 out of the hands of them that seek my soul, and from the gates of tribulations which have compassed me:
\v 6 from the oppression of the flame, which hath compassed me, and in the midst of fire I was not burnt.
\v 7 From the depth of the belly of hell, and from a defiled tongue, and from the word of lying, from a wicked king, and from an unjust tongue:
\v 8 my soul shall praise our Lord even to death,
\v 9 and my life was approaching to hell beneath.
\v 10 They have compassed me on every side, & there was none that would help. I looked toward the help of men, & there was none.
\v 11 I remembered thy mercy o Lord, and thy operation, which are from the beginning of the world.
\v 12 Because thou deliverest them that patiently expect thee o Lord, and savest them out of the hands of the nations.
\v 13 Thou hast exalted my habitation upon the earth, and I have prayed for death to pass away.
\v 14 I have invocated our Lord the father of my Lord, that he leave me not in the day of my tribulation, and in the time of the proud without help.
\v 15 I will praise thy name continually, and will collaud it in confession, and my prayer was heard.
\v 16 And thou hast delivered me from perdition, and hast rescued me from the wicked time.
\v 17 Therefore will I confess, & say praise to thee, and bless the name of our Lord.
\v 18 When I was yet young, before I erred, I sought for wisdom openly in my prayer. \f + \fr 51:18 \ft When senses are most ripe, and the soul most free from great sins, is the aptest time to serve God, & to get all virtues, and true knowledge. Eccle. 12.\f*
\v 19 Before the temple I prayed for it, and unto the later end I will seek after it, and it shall flourish as the grape timely ripe,
\v 20 my heart hath rejoiced in it, my foot hath walked the right way, from my youth I searched after it.
\v 21 I bowed mine ear a little, and received it.
\v 22 Ifound much wisdom in myself, & I have much profited therein.
\v 23 To him that giveth me wisdom, will I give glory.
\v 24 For I have consulted to do it: I have had a zeal to good, and shall not be confounded.
\v 25 My soul hath wrestled in it, and in doing it I was confirmed.
\v 26 Istretched forth my hands on high, & I lamented foolishness.
\v 27 I directed my soul to wisdom, and in knowledge I found it.
\v 28 I possessed with it an heart from the beginning: for this cause I shall not be forsaken.
\v 29 My belly was troubled in seeking it: therefore shall I possess a good possession.
\v 30 Our Lord hath given me a tongue for my reward: and with the same I will praise him.
\v 31 Approach unto me ye unlearned, and gather yourselves together into the house of discipline.
\v 32 Why slack ye yet? And what say you herein? Your souls are exceeding thirsty.
\v 33 I have opened my mouth, and have spoken: Buy it for you without silver,
\v 34 and submit your neck to the yoke, and let your soul receive discipline: for it is very near to find it.
\v 35 See with your eyes that I have laboured a little, and have found much rest to myself.
\v 36 Take ye discipline in a great sum of silver, and possess aboundance of gold in it. \f + \fr 51:36 \ft In stead of riches labour to get wisdom for it is much better than all gold & silver.\f*
\v 37 Let your soul rejoice in his mercy, and you shall not be confounded in praise.
\v 38 Work your work before the time, and he will give you your reward in his time. \f + \fr 51:38 \ft Merit is in this life, and reward in the next.\f*
